[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Caro-Kann: Introduction"]
[Black "1. Caveman introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5
{ The starting position of the Advance Caro-Kann.    3...c5  is the respected Botvinnik-Carls gambit, which we will consider in chapter 9. }
4. h4
{ Nowadays this is the second most popular move, after Nigel Short's invention 4. Nf3. It used to be that Alexey Shirov's 4. Nc3 was the most popular, but this move has really fallen into obscurity in the last decade. For example, in one database I use I can find 20 games with 4. Nc3 in 2018, where 4. h4 has more than 20 games in the final month of 2018 alone...   In any case, the move 4. h4 has several ideas. Firstly,   4...e6?  is temporarily prevented because  5.g4  would trap the f5-bishop. Most Caro-Kann players do want to keep their bishop outside the pawn chain, so they will either go 4... h5 or 4... h6 - the latter is considered in chapter 7. The move ...h6 is less weakening, but also allows White to grab more space with g4 and  (eventually)  h5. Hence most Caro-Kann players  (including myself)  prefer 4... h5. }
4... h5 5. Bg5
{ Here we diverge from the main line. 4. h4 players normally play 5. c4 at this point, and thus enter a sort of refined variation of 4. c4  (with the moves h4 h5 inserted)  . White will have some kind of space advantage, but Black has the typical Caro-Kann rock solid position with smooth development and  (nearly)  no weaknesses.  The Caveman move 5. Bg5 frustrates Black's development by preventing him from playing ...e6. In order to achieve ...e6 Black will now have to move his queen out instead.   Though I think  5...f6!?  is a very interesting try , even if it has never been played yet!  With White's b2-pawn looking appetizing, most black players go for 5... Qb6, which at the same time unpins the e7-pawn. }
5... Qb6 6. Bd3
{ What's this? Isn't the b2-pawn simply hanging? The Caveman isn't that invested in material. He prefers the speed of quick development. }
6... Bxd3
{ Black has two important alternatives at this point, notably   6...Qxb2  - chapter 3,  and   6...Qxd4  - chapter 4. }
7. Qxd3 Qxb2
{ Most black players who know the Caveman variation will play  7...e6  at this point. This move will be looked at in chapter 5 & 6 , 'The Caveman declined'. }
8. e6
{ A fantastic move! But isn't White hanging his a1-rook? Fortunately the position is not that simple.  First of all, anytime Black takes on a1, White will answer with Qb3! with which White not only protects his b1-knight, but also threatens to invade on b7 in turn.  Thanks to the e6-pawn such an invasion would not just threaten the a8-rook, but also mate on c8.  Should Black prevent Qxb7 by playing ...b6 or ...b5, White can then develop the g1-knight to f3 or e2, protecting the d4-pawn, and suddenly the queen on a1 is in danger of being trapped!  Meanwhile the e6-pawn throws a huge spanner in the works of the black kingside. Not only does Black have to take into account that White can displace his king with exf7+, but quite simply the development of Black's kingside is in complete disarray. Playing ...fxe6 means it will take several more moves for the f8-bishop to come out. Meanwhile White can post a knight on the e5-square and threaten all sort of things on the weakened light squares  (f7, g6)  .  Some statistics: the position after 6. Bd3 features in roughly 160 games in my database. 5 of those games continued with 6... Qxb2  (analysed in chapter 3)  . 22 games went 6... Qxd4  (chapter 4)  . 33 games featured 6... Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2  (chapter 2)  . The rest of the games by and large went 6... Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6  (the Caveman Declined, which is analyzed in chapters 5 and 6)  .  Disclaimer: Some of the chapters  (especially chapters 3, 4 and 6)  contain long variations in which exact play is required. These variations aren't theory, but they are indications of how White should play. I wanted to show that White gets good play for the sacrificed material in every variation, and sometimes I had to go very deep for that. In most cases the variations are useful to know though, as they illustrate typical ideas for White's position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: Mainline"]
[Black "2. The Caveman Mainline: 8... Qxa1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2 8. e6
Qxa1 9. Qb3
{ White defends the b1-knight and takes aim at the b7-pawn. At the same time he has ideas of trapping Black's queen. }
9... Qxd4
{ This is the only way Black can guarantee that his queen won't be trapped. }
10. Qxb7 { 10.Be3  immediately is also strong and should transpose. } 10...
fxe6 { Note  10...Qb6?  11.Qc8+!  Qd8  12.exf7+  and Black loses his queen. }
11. Be3
{ 11.Qxa8?  Qb6!  is less clear.  With the text White wins a tempo on Black's queen, prevents ...Qb6, and finally prepares the idea of Qxa8 followed by Bxa7 picking up the b8-knight. }
11... Qa4
{ The game Weggen - van der Heide  (2018)   went  11...Qa1  12.Nf3!  Kf7  13.O-O  and White can pick up the a8-rook next with a winning position. }
12. Qxa8 Qa5+ 13. Nd2 Qd8 14. Ngf3
{ White's development is harmonious and easy, while Black's position is full of holes and he won't be able to satisfactorily develop the kingside. }
14... Nf6 15. O-O g6 16. Rb1 { And White wins material as simple as that! }
16... Nbd7 { 16...Nfd7  17.Bxa7  Na6  18.Qxc6  and the a6-knight is lost. } 17.
Qxc6 Bg7 18. Ng5 { Black resigned here in Perunovic - Lalith  (Dubai 2009)  . }
18... O-O 19. Qxe6+ Kh8 20. Nf7+ Rxf7 21. Qxf7
{ White is up an exchange and Black's position is still full of weaknesses. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
