1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2 8. e6
Qxa1 9. Qb3 b5 10. Nf3 a5 11. O-O a4 12. exf7+
{ This is a tactical alternative to the more methodical  12.Qa3. } 12... Kxf7
{ 12...Kd8  of course allows  13.fxg8=Q. } 13. Ne5+ Ke8 14. Qh3
{ Suddenly White has a winning attack. } 14... Kd8 15. Nf7+ Kc7
{ 15...Ke8?  16.Nd6+!  exd6  17.Re1+  leads to mate. } 16. Bf4+ Kb6 17. Qc8
{ White has a winning attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: Mainline"]
[Black "8. The Caveman Mainline: 8... Qxa1 and 9... Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2 8. e6
Qxa1 9. Qb3 Nf6 10. Nf3
{ White should answer this move in the same way as 9... b5. } 10... b5 11. O-O
Ne4 { This aims to prevent Nc3 and/or Nbd2. } 12. Bd2
{ A nice move found by Michael Goeller. White intends to play Bc3 to trap Black's queen. }
12... Nc5 { 12...a5  13.Bc3  a4  14.Qa3!  and White wins. } 13. dxc5
{ This is the most straightforward option. } 13... Qf6
{ The only move. Black is now an exchange up but he has huge development problems as well as various weaknesses. }
14. Re1
{ As always, White should let Black cripple his own kingside with ...fxe6. }
14... fxe6 15. Bg5 Qf7 16. Nd4
{ White should waste no time to exploit Black's weaknesses on e6 and c6. }
16... e5 17. Rxe5 Nd7 18. Re6 Rc8 19. Qa3
{ White can finish his development with Nd2-f3 and then decisively penetrate on a7 or a6 with his queen. }
