[Black "9. The Caveman Mainline: 8... f6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2 8. e6
f6 9. Nf3
{ Retreating with  9.Bd2  would be insipid. White must develop as fast as possible! }
9... fxg5 10. O-O Rh6
{ This seems stronger than Goeller's suggested move  10...gxh4  which is analyzed in line 10. }
11. hxg5 Rxe6
{ The rook has eliminated White's e6-pawn, but it has a shaky position in the middle of the board. }
12. Nbd2 { Threatening Rfb1 trapping Black's queen. } 12... Qb6
{ 12...Qb5  13.Qf5!  Rd6  14.Qc8+  Rd8  15.Qe6!  White picks up the g8-knight while maintaining a strong initiative  (he is already threatening a combination of Qg6+ and Ne5)  (.) }
13. Rab1 Qc7 14. Qf5 { Winning a tempo on the poorly positioned rook. } 14...
Re2
{ 14...Rd6  15.Ne5  is similar.   14...Qd7  15.Rxb7!  Qxb7  16.Qxe6  and White picks up the g8-knight next with a dominant position. }
15. Ne5
{ White has a decisive attack. Black can hardly deal with the threat of Qf7+. }
15... Rxe5 16. dxe5 Na6 17. Qg6+ Kd7 18. e6+ Kc8 19. Qf7
{ White picks up the g8-knight. The more aggressively inclined can play  19.c4!?  instead. }
