[Black "9.5 The Caveman Mainline: 8... f6, 10... Qxa1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2 8. e6
f6 9. Nf3
{ Retreating with  9.Bd2  would be insipid. White must develop as fast as possible! }
9... fxg5 10. O-O Qxa1
{ Of course we should also take a look at what happens when Black grabs as much material as he can. }
11. Qb3
{ This standard move attacks b7 and prepares to pick up Black's queen with Nbd2 or Nc3. }
11... b5 12. Nc3 Qxf1+ 13. Kxf1
{ Time to make up the balance. Black has two rooks and a bishop for the queen, but he is severely behind in development  (even more so than in the 'regular' Caveman where Black only gets two rooks for his queen)  , and completely locked up. It's not hard for Stockfish to conclude that White is easily winning. To start with, White is threatening both 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Qxd5 and 14. Nxb5 cxb5 15. Qxd5. }
13... g4
{ 13...Nf6  doesn't help:  14.hxg5  Ne4  15.Nxe4  dxe4  16.Ne5  and Black can't do anything about the threat of Nxc6 followed by Qd5. A sample line:  16...g6  17.Nxc6 !  Bg7  18.Qd5  O-O  19.Nxe7+  Kh7  20.Qxe4  and Stockfish announces mate in  10. }
14. Ne5 { Black can't cope with the threats against c6, b5 and d5. } 14... a6
15. Nxc6 Nf6 { 15...Nxc6  16.Qxd5  threatens both Qd7# and Qxc6+. } 16. Ne5
{ This seems the most straight-forward: The knight is dominant on e5 and Black still can't defend his weaknesses on b5 and d5 properly. }
16... g6 { This is far too late. } 17. Nxb5 axb5 18. Qc3
{ 18.Qxb5+  is also decisive, but 18. Qc3 is the fastest way to mate.  The threat is 19. Qc8# and   18...Kd8  19.Nf7+  doesn't help. }
18... Na6
{ 18...Nbd7  holds out the longest , but White also mates after  19.exd7+  Nxd7  20.Qc6 ! }
19. Qc6+ Kd8 20. Nf7# *

