1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2 8. e6
fxe6 9. Nf3
{ If Black delays taking the a1-rook White should simply play Nf3 and castle kingside. White does not hurry with Qg6+ as Black has no way to prevent it anyway, and long castling by Black would be welcomed as then White can use the half-open b-file for the attack. }
9... Nd7 10. O-O Qxa1 11. Qb3 { Trapping Black's queen. } 11... e5 12. Nc3
Qxf1+ 13. Kxf1 e4 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Qxb7
{ An important in-between move. Black resigned here in Firman - Makarov  (Alushta 2006)  , but it is worth looking at what would have happened next. }
15... Rd8 16. dxe5 { Now Black has no way to protect the c6-pawn. } 16... g6
17. Qxc6+ Kf7 18. Ne2
{ An instructive move. White notices that the g6-pawn cannot be defended. }
18... Bg7 19. Nf4
{ Black must give up a lot of material to prevent being mated. } *

