1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2 8. e6
fxe6 9. Nf3 Nd7 10. O-O
{ As usual, if Black delays taking the rook White should simply play Nf3 and castle kingside. White does not hurry with Qg6+ as Black has no way to prevent it anyway, and long castling by Black would be welcomed as then White can use the half-open b-file for the attack. }
10... Qxa1 11. Qb3 { Trapping Black's queen. } 11... e5 12. Nc3 Qxf1+ 13. Kxf1
Rb8 14. Nxe5
{ 14.dxe5  is fine too. With the text White clears the 3rd rank so that after the c3-knight moves White's queen can swing over to the h3-square if necessary. }
14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 e6 16. Ne2
{ White clears the 3rd rank for his queen while directing the knight to f4 to target the weaknesses e6 and g6. }
16... Ne7 17. Qa3
{ With the decisive threats of Qxa7 and Qd6  (forking b8 and e6)  .   Also good is  17.Nd4  Kd7  18.Qh3  winning material. }
