[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxb2
{ This amounts to an exchange sacrifice for White. } 7. Bxf5 Qxa1 8. e6
{ Otherwise Black would shore up his position with ...e6, and White's compensation for the exchange would be dubious. }
8... Nh6 9. exf7+ Nxf7 10. Bg6 { Limiting Black's options. } 10... Nd7 11. Nf3
e5
{ Black will eventually have to move his e-pawn in order to get his kingside in the game. Note that Black cannot castle queenside because White will simply pick up the f7-knight. }
12. O-O
{ White needs to be careful here. After  12.dxe5?  Ndxe5  suddenly Black's pieces untangle and his queen joins the defense on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
12... Bd6
{ 12...e4?!  13.Qd2!  (threatening Qf4)  Bd6  14.c4!  exf3  15.Nc3  and Black's queen is trapped. }
13. Bd2
{ This threatens both Ng5, which wins material on f7, and Bc3 followed by dxe5.   13.dxe5  is an interesting alternative. }
13... O-O
{ It is hard to say what else Black should play. Note  13...exd4  14.Qe2+!  Kf8   14...Kd8  15.Bxf7  and White has won a piece  15.Qe6!  and Black is soon mated! }
14. Bc3 Qxa2 15. dxe5 Bxe5
{ 15...Be7  allows  16.e6  Nh8  17.Qd3!  Nf6  18.Ng5!  with a decisive attack. }
16. Bxf7+ Rxf7 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5
{ The position has become materially balanced. Black's a-pawn is passed and can become a nuisance, but on the other hand it is hard to say what Black can do against a simple attacking plan by White: f4, Nd2-f3-g5 and Qxh5. If Black defends with ...g6, White can target the newly created weakness with Qd3 and Nd2-f3-d4.  In any case, Black lacks good open files for his rooks, while both of White's minor pieces will find strong squares. }
