1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxb2 7. Bxf5 Qxa1 8. e6
fxe6 9. Bg6+ Kd8 10. Nf3
{ When Black plays ...fxe6 it is a good idea to try to exploit the e5-square. }
10... Nd7 11. O-O Ngf6 12. Qe2
{ Preparing Nbd2  (which attacks the Black queen)  and focusing on Black's weaknesses on the e-file. }
12... Qxa2 13. Qxe6 Rh6
{ Black offers the exchange back because otherwise he will never untangle his kingside. }
14. Bxh6 gxh6 15. Bf5
{ White is now two pawns behind, but he still has excellent compensation. There are opposite-colored bishops on the board, and in such positions what matters is who has the initiative, not who has a couple of extra pawns.  White's direct plan is to play Ne5 to pile up on d7. Black cannot reply ...Nxe5 because after dxe5 his f6-knight is hanging, but at the same time it must protect against Qd7+. }
15... Kc7 16. Ne5 Rd8
{ 16...Nxe5?  17.dxe5  Ne4  18.Qd7+  Kb6  19.Bxe4!  dxe4  20.Nc3!  and the threat of Rb1 is decisive. }
17. Nd2
{ White simply brings in the reserves as Black's pieces are totally tied down. }
17... Qa4
{ Notice the clever idea of  17...a5?!  18.Ne4!!  Nxe4  19.Nxd7  and White is winning.   17...Kb8  18.Ne4! }
18. Nb3 Kb8 19. Nxd7+ Nxd7 20. Qf7
{ Black is still completely tied down - his rook cannot move, his bishop cannot move, and if the knight moves White will play Nc5-e6 winning material.   A possible continuation is  20...e6  21.Bxe6  Nb6  22.Nc5  Bxc5  23.dxc5  Na8  24.Qe7  Qa5  25.Rb1  Qc7  26.Qf6  White will restore material equality by taking on h6 while keeping a dominant position. }
