[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: 6... Qxd4"]
[Black "30. The Caveman 6... Qxd4: 7... Qxb2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4
{ This move either leads to a pawn sacrifice after 7... Qg4, or a pawn plus exchange sacrifice after 7... Qxb2.  Note: the lines in this chapter were some of the hardest to find something favorable for White, so I am eager to share my ideas and analysis! }
7. Nf3
{ White needs to be careful that he doesn't play  7.Bxf5?  Qxe5+!  and Black regains the piece with a clear advantage. }
7... Qxb2
{ It seems illogical to first lose a tempo by taking the d4-pawn, and then go for the a1-rook anyway. However, it is very difficult to refute this move! }
8. Bxf5 Qxa1 9. e6
{ In essence this is the 6... Qxb2 variation, except White's knight is already on f3 and his d4-pawn is gone. This difference does not directly favor White, though of course we welcome the faster development! }
9... fxe6 10. Bxe6
{ In the previous chapter we saw ...fxe6 being answered by Bg6+, but in this position I prefer Bxe6. After Bg6+ Black would have a big pawn center and it would be difficult to activate our queen. On e6 the light-squared bishop dominates Black's position. White's queen can go to d3  (or c2)  to threaten Qg6+ and we can play c4xd5 to further chip at Black's center. }
10... Nd7 11. Bxd7+
{ White abandons his strong bishop very fast, but he exchanges a strong defender and now Black's king has to wander over the board. }
11... Kxd7 12. O-O Nf6 13. Qd3 { Preparing Nc3. } 13... Qxa2 14. Ne5+ Kc7
{ Black's king has no real good squares. Kd8 or Kd6 is answered by Nf7+, while ...Kc8 allows Qf5+ or Qh3+ at some point. }
15. Bf4 Re8 16. Nc3
{ Not  16.Ng6+?  e5!  17.Bxe5+  Rxe5!  and Black is better. White has to wait for the right moment for the discovered check! }
16... Qa6 17. Qf5 { Now White is finally well-positioned for Ng6+ or Nf7+. }
17... Kb8 18. Ng6+ Ka8 19. Nxh8
{ The position is still highly unclear. White has a piece for three pawns, but arguably his pieces are better developed. }
*

