12... Bd6 13. Qb3 { Now Black is in danger of having the a1-queen trapped. }
13... Nd7 { 13...e4?  14.O-O!  exf3?  15.Re1+  and White has a mating attack. }
14. O-O Nc5 15. Qc2 { Now Black has no way to stop Nbd2 trapping his queen. }
15... e4 16. Nbd2 Qxf1+ 17. Kxf1 exf3 18. Nxf3
{ Material is roughly balanced, but White's pieces are positioned much better and Black's king is unsafe. }
18... O-O { Attempting to bring the king to safety, but it fails. } 19. Bh7+
Kh8 20. Qg6 { White will follow up with Qxh5 with a winning attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: 6... Qxd4"]
[Black "35. The Caveman 6... Qxd4: 7... Qxb2, 9... Nh6 and 10... Kxf7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qxb2 8. Bxf5
Qxa1 9. e6 Nh6 10. exf7+ Kxf7 11. Bh3
{ Keeping an eye on e6.   After  11.Bd3  e5!  White would have to reckon with ...e4 when he has to sacrifice even more material. }
11... Ng4
{ This way Black tries to block the h3-bishop's diagonal. However, at some point White will be able to play f3 chasing the g4-knight away. }
12. O-O Nd7 13. Qd3 { eyeing the f5-square. } 13... Qb2 14. Qf5+ Ke8
{ 14...Ndf6  15.Bf4!  the usual maneuver that vacates the g5-square for a knight  Qb6  16.Ng5+  Ke8  17.Qg6+  Kd7  18.Nd2!  with ideas like Rb1 and Nc4 dxc4 Rd1+. White is already winning according to the engine. }
15. Nbd2 Qb6 16. Nb3
{ Intending to play a knight to d4 and then e6.  As usual, the engine very slowly comes around to the fact that White has very promising compensation for his material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: 6... Qxd4"]
[Black "36. The Caveman 6... Qxd4: 7... Qg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qg4
{ This is considered stronger than 7... Qxb2. Black satisfies himself with the win of a single pawn, after which he still has a very solid position - a hard nut to crack for White! }
8. Bxf5
{ This pulls Black's queen slightly out of position; she is better stationed on g4. }
8... Qxf5 9. c4
{ This is my recommendation. Goeller discusses 9. Qe2 and 9. O-O, but against both of those moves I can't find any advantage for White after the bold 9... f6!   For example:  9.O-O  f6!  10.exf6  gxf6  11.Be3  e5!  12.c4  d4  13.Bxd4  (this piece sac is more or less forced)  exd4  14.Nxd4  and White would have good compensation were it not for the fact that Black has the annoying  14...Qg4! }
9... Qe4+ { Of course, Black picking up the c4-pawn is critical. } 10. Be3 Qxc4
11. e6
{ One of the main ideas of 9. c4. If Black immediately goes for the c4-pawn, we get to play the typical Caveman move again! }
11... fxe6 12. Nbd2 Qb4 13. Qc2 Nf6 14. Ne5
{ Black is already struggling for good moves. The direct threat is Qg6+ Kd8 Nf7+. }
14... Rg8 15. a3
{ An important move - White takes control over the a5-e1 diagonal. } 15... Qb5
16. Ndf3 Ne4 17. Ng5 Nxg5 18. Qg6+ Kd8 19. hxg5
{ Now Black has a big problem - there is no good way to prevent Qh7xg8  (...Rh8 is met by Nf7+)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: 6... Qxd4"]
[Black "37. The Caveman 6... Qxd4: 7... Qg4 and 9... e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qg4 8. Bxf5
Qxf5 9. c4 e6
{ Of course we should check out what White should do after this solid move. }
10. O-O
{ White should wait with cxd5 until Black has committed his b8-knight to d7 so that he cannot develop it to c6. }
10... Ne7
{ Another possible line is  10...Nd7  11.cxd5  cxd5  12.Nc3  a6  13.Qb3  b5?!  14.Nxd5!  exd5  15.Qxd5  Rb8  16.Nd4  followed by e6 and White has a very strong attack. }
11. Qb3 { Taking aim at the weak b7-pawn. } 11... b6 12. Nc3 Nd7 13. Rad1
{ White prepares to play Nd4. } 13... Nc5 14. Qa3 dxc4 15. Rd6
{ Another interesting idea is  15.Na4!?  Nd5  16.Nxb6!!  Nd7   16...Nxb6?  17.Qxa7!  and the queen is immune because of  Rd8  mate.  17.Qa4!  N5xb6  18.Qxc6  and Black cannot really meet the threat of Rxd7. Thus White wins back his piece with interest. }
15... a5 { Almost any move by the e7-knight would allow Qxa7! } 16. Be3
{ Threatening to take on c5. } 16... Nd7 17. Rxd7 Kxd7 18. Qd6+ Ke8 19. Rd1
{ White has a winning initiative. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: 6... Qxd4"]
[Black "38. The Caveman 6... Qxd4: 7... Qg4, 9... e6 and 10... Nd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qg4 8. Bxf5
Qxf5 9. c4 e6 10. O-O Nd7 11. cxd5
{ As a general rule, once Black has committed his queenside knight to d7 it is good to take on d5. }
11... cxd5
{ Now Black cannot develop a knight to the fantastic c6-square in one go. } 12.
Nc3 a6 { This is necessary because Nb5 would be a major problem for Black. }
13. Qb3 { Attacking the b7-weakness. } 13... b5
{ This allows a typical piece sac. } 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Qxd5 Rb8 16. Nd4 Ne7
{ Black can save his position with this clever move.   16...Qg6?  17.e6!  fxe6  18.Nxe6  and White comes crashing through. }
17. Bxe7 Qxe5
{ This is the point - Black forces the exchange of queens by giving back the piece. }
18. Qxe5 Nxe5 19. Rfe1
{ However, White still has an initiative in this endgame. } 19... f6 20. Bxf8
{ Not  20.f4?  Bxe7  21.fxe5  Bc5!  and Black is better. } 20... Kxf8 21. Rad1
{ White will follow up with f4, Ne6  (+)  and Rd7 with a clear advantage in the endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: 6... Qxd4"]
[Black "39. The Caveman 6... Qxd4: 7... Qg4, 9... e6 and 13... Rb8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qg4 8. Bxf5
Qxf5 9. c4 e6 10. O-O Nd7 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nc3 a6 13. Qb3 Rb8
{ This is definitely stronger than 13... b5. } 14. Rac1
{ White should simply deploy his rooks  (c1, d1 and e1 are all good squares for them)  and wait to see how Black develops. Sometimes White can sacrifice a piece on d5, sometimes he can play Ne2-d4. In any case he has good compensation for the pawn. Black's main issue is that he lacks space to develop both the f8-bishop and the g8-knight smoothly. }
14... Ne7 15. Rfd1 Nc6 16. Nxd5 { Again we see this typical piece sacrifice. }
16... exd5 17. Rxd5 { White is threatening e6. } 17... Nc5 18. Qb6 Qe4
{ Black hardly has a good move.  18...Ne6?  would be met by  19.Rxc6! } 19.
Rdxc5 Bxc5 20. Qxc5
{ White has a pawn and a lead in development for the exchange. } 20... Qb4 21.
Qc2 O-O 22. Be3
{ This threatens both Bc5 and Ng5 g6 e6! with a strong attack. White has excellent compensation for the exchange. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: 6... Qxd4"]
[Black "40. The Caveman 6... Qxd4: 7... Qg4, 9... Qe4+ and 11... Bb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qg4 8. Bxf5
Qxf5 9. c4 Qe4+ 10. Be3 e6
{ This line is recommended in the course 'The Modernized Caro-Kann' by GM Daniel Fernandez, but he does not consider 11. Nbd2. }
11. Nbd2 { Winning a tempo on Black's queen. } 11... Bb4
{ Black often lacks space to develop his kingside, so it is a good idea of him to get rid of the bishop as soon as possible.  A game Francisco - Vigorito  (Charlotte 2017)   continued  11...Qd3  12.Rc1  dxc4; See line 41. }
12. O-O { Simply developing. } 12... Bxd2 13. Qxd2 Qxc4
{ Otherwise White will play b3 followed by Bg5 with good compensation for the pawn. }
14. Rac1 Qg4 15. Qa5 { Thus White penetrates the queenside. } 15... Na6
{ 15...b6  16.Bxb6.   15...Nd7  16.Qc7  and White at the very least wins the b7-pawn. }
16. Rxc6 bxc6 17. Qxa6 Qc4 18. Qb7 Rd8 19. Nd4 { This prevents ...Qb5. } 19...
Ne7 20. Rc1
{ Black is 1 tempo short of castling. White's attack is just in time!   After  20...Qxa2  21.Nxc6  Nxc6  22.Qxc6+  Kf8  23.Bg5!  White has a winning attack. }
*

