[White "The Caveman Accepted: 6... Qxd4"]
[Black "43. The Caveman 6... Qxd4: 7... Qg4, 9... Qe4+ and 11... Qd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qg4 8. Bxf5
Qxf5 9. c4 Qe4+ 10. Be3 e6 11. Nbd2 Qd3 12. Rc1 dxc4
{ Thus far the game Francisco - Vigorito  (Charlotte 2017)  . } 13. Rxc4 Ne7
14. Rd4 Qa6 15. Nc4
{ Threatening Nd6+ and blocking the a6-f1 diagonal, so White can castle next move. }
15... Nd5 16. O-O Bc5 { This looks good, but it's actually bait. } 17. Ng5 Nd7
{ 17...Bxd4?!  18.Nd6+  Ke7  19.Bxd4  and White has massive compensation for the exchange. }
18. Re4 Be7
{ 18...Nxe3?  19.fxe3  and Black cannot prevent the move Nxf7 next. } 19. Qf3
Rf8 20. Qxh5 { White has regained the pawn with an advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Accepted: 6... Qxd4"]
[Black "44. The Caveman 6... Qxd4: 7... Qg4 and 9... f6!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qg4 8. Bxf5
Qxf5 9. c4 f6
{ Of course, if this move gave me headaches after White's alternatives on move 9  (O-O and Qe2)  , then we should look at it here as well! }
10. Be3
{ White can simply retreat and let his e5-pawn hang because Black's d5-pawn in turn is also hanging. }
10... e6 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. Qb3 b6 13. O-O { 13.Nc3  is a good alternative. }
13... Nbd7 14. Nd4 { Forking c6 and f5. } 14... Qg4 15. f3
{ White encourages Black to take on h4 so that White's knight can take on e6 in turn. }
15... Qg3 16. Bf2
{ White needs to be careful:  16.Nxe6?  Bd6!  and Black has a strong attack. }
16... Qd6 17. cxd5 Nxd5 18. Nc3 Nc5 19. Qc2
{ In return for the pawn White has good development. Black has various weaknesses and his king won't be safe on either queenside or kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Declined: Mainline"]
[Black "45. The Caveman Declined: 8... Qxb2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nd2
{ I am going against Goeller's recommendation here, which is 8. Nc3. I do not believe White can hope for an advantage or play actively after 8. Nc3 - I think White needs the c2-c4 break to be able to do that, and the knight on c3 blocks that pawn break. }
8... Qxb2 { Of course, we have to check out this pawn-grabbing move. } 9. Rb1
Qxa2
{ 9...Qa3  10.Qxa3  Bxa3  11.Rh3!  Bf8  12.Rxb7  with an advantage to White in Kislinsky - Grinev , Kiev 2006. }
10. Rxb7
{ It turns out Black has big problems developing his kingside - business as usual in the Caveman! }
10... Ne7 11. Ngf3 Nf5 12. O-O Be7 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Qc3 { Threatening Ra1. }
14... Qa6 15. Qb2 { With the dual threat of Rxb8+ and Ra1. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Declined: Mainline"]
[Black "46. The Caveman Declined: 8... Ne7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nd2
Ne7 9. Ne2 { This is usually more flexible than Ngf3 in this variation. } 9...
Nf5 10. O-O Nd7 11. c4 Bb4 12. cxd5
{ White releases the tension because he sees that he can make use of the precarious position of the b4-bishop. }
12... cxd5 { Notice  12...Bxd2?  13.dxe6! } 13. Nf3 O-O 14. a3 Be7 15. Ng3
{ Now White achieves favorable exchanges on the kingside. } 15... Nxg3 16. fxg3
Rfe8 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Rf2 { White has a strong attacking position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Declined: Mainline"]
[Black "47. The Caveman Declined: 8... Ne7 and 11... Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nd2
Ne7 9. Ne2 Nf5 10. O-O Nd7 11. c4 Be7 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Nf4
{ Making it difficult for Black to decide where to put his king. } 13... Nf5
{ This leads to a forcing variation.   13...O-O-O?!  14.c5  and White can start a pawn storm on the queenside. }
14. cxd5 Qxd4 { 14...cxd5?!  15.Nxd5. } 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. Qxd4 Nxd4 17. Nc4
{ White has an advantage in development, and - more importantly - a better pawn structure. }
*

