c5 9. c4 Nc6 10. Ngf3 Nge7 11. dxc5 Qxb2
{ This reckless pawn-grab is Black's only real alternative to 11... Qxc5. } 12.
O-O Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Rfe1 Qf5
{ 14...Qc7  15.cxd5  is problematic for Black due to the pin on the e-file. }
15. Qb3 { The b7-weakness is a recurring theme. } 15... f6 16. cxd5
{ A strong piece sacrifice. } 16... fxg5 17. Nc4 { Threatening Nd6+. } 17...
Nxd5 18. Qb5+
{ White gives an in-between check to force Black's king to an unfortunate position. }
18... Kf7 19. Qxb7+ Kg8 20. Qxa8 { White has a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Declined: 9... Qxb2"]
[Black "53. The Caveman Declined: 9... Qxb2, 10... Qxd4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nd2
c5 9. c4 Qxb2
{ This move is quite critical. The main issue is that White has to deal with the possibility of ...Qxd4 when Black will be up two pawns - which is fine, but White needs serious compensation for the material! }
10. Rd1
{ There have been games with 10. Rb1, but in my view the rook is better positioned on d1 to discourage ...Qxd4 and, should Black take the pawn anyway, make use of the semi-open d-file. Meanwhile, White's queen will  (if Black plays ...Qxd4)  go to b3 to harass b7. }
10... Qxd4
{ Black is rather greedy! The text is a minor but critical option. Later we will take a look at 10... Nc6 which is more dangerous.    10...Qxa2  and   10...Ne7  do not have independent value, as sooner or later Black will have to play ...Nc6 and transpose. }
11. Qb3 Qxe5+
{ Black has no real alternatives here, since other moves  (such as ...b6 or ...Nd7)  allow Ngf3 followed by cxd5 when White already takes over the initiative. }
12. Ne2 b6 { Better is  12...Qc7. } 13. cxd5 Qxd5
{ After  13...exd5  14.O-O  White will bring a rook to the e-file with a winning advantage. }
14. Nf3 Qxb3 15. Rd8# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman Declined: 9... Qxb2"]
