[White "The Caveman: 4... h6"]
[Black "71. The Caveman 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 and 7... Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6
{ Not at all a bad move, at least if Black intends to follow up with 5. g4 Bd7!. Black wants to lure White into playing g4 when he retreats the bishop back to d7, playing ...e6 and ...c5. He will play the position like a French defense in which White has already committed his pawns on the kingside forward - the question is whether these pawns constitute a weakness or a strength. }
5. g4 { We take the 'bait'. } 5... Bd7
{ Alternatively Black can try to keep his bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal, but that will repeatedly run into the pawn sacrifice e6! by White as we will see later. }
6. Nc3
{ The main move here is   6.h5  which cements White's space advantage on the kingside and prevents black from playing ...h5. However, after  6...c5!  Black is doing quite well - White is perhaps making too many pawn moves. The text gives Black more options such as ...h5 but it accelerates White's development. }
6... e6 { Black has various alternatives here that we will look at. } 7. Be3
Qb6
{ Again, Black has other possible moves:   7...c5  ,   7...h5.   7...Qc7  has little independent value as Black will soon play  ..c5  transposing to  7...c5. }
8. Nge2
{ 8.Qd2  Qxb2  9.Rb1  Qa3  10.Rxb7?!  Bb4!  is a bit difficult for White to deal with , as after  11.Nge2  Na6  his rook will be trapped. }
8... c5
{ Now  8...Qxb2?!  9.Rb1  Qa3  10.Rxb7  Bb4  is less strong because of  11.Bd2  Na6  12.Rh3!  and the h-rook decisively joins the battle. }
9. Qd2 Nc6 10. f4
{ White does best to delay castling , as after  10.O-O-O  c4!?  he may be subject to a pawn storm on the queenside. The text prepares the push  f5  , but also simply taking on  c5  followed by long castling works here too.  The position now resembles the Steinitz variation of the French Defense   1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.f4  c5  ,  the key struggle being around the d4-square. }
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bc5 13. Bxc5
{ This seems stronger to me than  13.O-O-O  Bxd4  14.Qxd4  Qxd4  15.Rxd4  Ne7  when the endgame looks rather equal , although White eventually ground out a win in Grandelius - Hillarp Persson  (Stockholm 2014)  (.) }
13... Qxc5 14. h5
{ White can continue with  O-O-O.  He has a pleasant space advantage. Notice that  14...d4?  is not a threat because of  15.Ne4  and the knight comes to d6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: 4... h6"]
[Black "72. The Caveman 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 and 7... c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bd7 6. Nc3 e6 7. Be3 c5 8. dxc5 Qc7
{ 8...Nc6  9.Nf3  and it is not clear how Black will regain his pawn. } 9. Qd2
Bxc5
{ If   9...Qxe5  Black will have to lose time because his queen on e5 will soon come under attack. For example  10.Nf3  White has many good alternatives here  Qc7  11.Nb5!?  Bxb5  12.Bxb5+  Nc6  13.Bf4  Qc8  14.Ne5  Nf6   14...Bxc5 ?  is impossible because of  15.Qc3 !  15.f3  and White has a bind on the position. }
10. f4 { White has the typical space advantage. } 10... Bxe3
{ Black had to move or exchange this bishop before he is able to play ...Nbc6. }
11. Qxe3 h5 { This looks strong, but it is not at all a problem for White. }
12. gxh5
{ The weaknesses of f7 and g7 will turn out to be more important than the f5- and h5-squares that Black obtains. }
12... Ne7 13. Bd3 { Of course, we don't allow ...Nf5. } 13... Rxh5 14. O-O-O a6
{ Black has to make this move to prevent Nb5-d6 if he wants to play ...Nbc6. }
15. Nf3 Nbc6
{ This was Florstedt - Starostits  (Berlin 2018)  . Now strongest to me seems the following. }
16. Qg1 { Attacking g7. } 16... g6 17. Ng5
{ The attack on f7 prevents Black from castling long. } 17... Rh8 18. h5
{ A strong temporary pawn sacrifice. } 18... gxh5 19. Qf2
{ White intends Be2xh5. Meanwhile Black has no good way to solve his development problems. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: 4... h6"]
[Black "73. The Caveman 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 and 7... h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bd7 6. Nc3 e6 7. Be3 h5
{ This is always an option White has to reckon with in the 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 variation when White does not play an early h5. }
8. gxh5
{ The most important thing to remember is that in response to ...h5 you rarely, if ever, want to move the pawn to g5. In this case Black would go   8.g5?  g6!  and the kingside is eternally blocked, rendering White's space advantage useless, while Black has a nice square on f5 for his knight. }
8... Nh6 9. Bh3
{ We don't allow  ..Nf5  to go unchallenged.  9.Bd3  is also possible but it removes the control of White's queen over  d4. }
9... c5 10. dxc5 Bc6
{ This is Morozevich - Bologan  (Astana 2012)  . Now the following seems strongest to me. }
11. Bd4
{ Blocking the ...d4 advance and keeping the c5- and e5-pawns protected. }
11... Nd7 12. b4 a6
{ Black would like to play  12...b6  breaking up White's queenside pawns , but unfortunately that runs into  13.b5!  and White wins a piece. }
13. a4 { Again threatening b5! } 13... Nxe5 14. b5
{ 14.Bxe5?!  d4  and Black regains the piece with a decent position. } 14...
Qa5 15. bxc6 Nxc6 16. Ne2 e5 17. Be3 d4
{ Black seems to regain the piece, but this leads to a nice refutation. } 18.
Bd2 { 18.Bxh6  Rxh6  19.Kf1  Qxc5  is also good for White , but less clear. }
18... dxc3 { Otherwise White will play Ne4 next. } 19. Bd7+ Ke7
{ 19...Kxd7  20.Bxc3+  wins the a5-queen thanks to the discovered check.   19...Kd8  20.Bxc3  Qc7  21.Bxc6+  and White stays a piece ahead. }
20. Bg5+ f6 21. Qd5 { The threat of Qe6# is decisive. } 21... Nd8 22. Nf4
{ Threatening Ng6#. } 22... exf4 23. O-O-O
{ A rook will come to e1 and mate soon follows. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: 4... h6"]
[Black "74. The Caveman 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 and 6... Qc8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Qc8
{ This move intends to lure the f1-bishop to an inferior square before playing the usual moves of ...e6 and ...c5. }
7. Bh3 { The e2-square should be reserved for the g1-knight. } 7... e6
{ Two games went  7...h5  8.gxh5  Nh6  9.Bxd7+  Qxd7  10.Bxh6!  Rxh6  11.Qf3!  and White had control over the kingside. It is nearly impossible for Black to regain the h5-pawn and White has the simple plan of developing pressure against the f7-pawn by bringing a knight to  g5  and his rooks to the f-file. }
8. Be3 c5 9. dxc5
{ The game Delaney - Parligras  (Novi Sad 2016)   went  9.Nge2  Nc6  10.f4  cxd4  11.Nxd4  Bb4  12.Qd3  Na5  and Black had good play with ..Nc4 coming. In my view White should keep the g1-knight on e2 so that it  (over)  protects the c3-knight. }
9... Bxc5 10. Qd2
{ Now White can just develop normally - Qd2, Nge2, f4, et cetera. } 10... Bb4
11. Nge2 Nc6 12. f4 Na5 13. b3 { Now White does not have to fear ..Nc4. } 13...
Qc7 14. a3 Bf8 { 14...Bxc3  15.Nxc3  Rc8  16.Bd4  Nc6?!  17.Nb5! } 15. h5
{ White has strong control over the position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: 4... h6"]
[Black "75. The Caveman 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 and 6... Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Qb6
{ Moving the queen to b6 this early is rather committal and slow. There are moves that have a higher priority! }
7. h5
{ If Black is doing nothing aggressive then this is a useful move.  7.Na4  is also possible , but perhaps Black can play  7...Qa5+  8.c3  h5!?  9.gxh5  Bf5. }
7... e6 8. Na4
{ Black is going to play ...c5 anyway, so it is a good idea to 1  move the knight from away from c3 so that you can move a pawn to c3, and 2  control the c5-square with the knight. }
8... Qa5+
{ 8...Qc7  9.Be3  c5  10.Nxc5  Bxc5  11.dxc5  Qxe5  12.Nf3  and White will play Bd4 next. }
9. c3 c5
{ If this move is necessary , Black's strategy has failed. But after  9...b5  10.Nc5!  Bxc5  11.dxc5  White also establishes control over the dark squares. }
10. Nxc5 Bxc5 11. dxc5 Qxc5 12. Be3 Qc7 13. f4 Ne7 14. Nf3
{ White had an ideal position in Vitiugov - Popov  (Jurmala 2016)  . His dark-squared bishop is unopposed. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: 4... h6"]
[Black "76. The Caveman 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 and 6... h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bd7 6. Nc3 h5 7. gxh5
{ The standard response to ...h5. } 7... Bf5 { This is rather slow. } 8. Bh3
Qd7 { 8...Bh7  9.e6!  is a thorn in Black's kingside. } 9. Qf3
{ This way White takes control over the kingside. } 9... Bxh3
{ 9...Nh6  10.Bxh6  should transpose. } 10. Nxh3 Nh6 11. Bxh6
{ This not only speeds up development, but also prevents Black from playing the knight to f5. }
11... Rxh6 12. O-O-O e6 13. Ng5
{ Now White has a very simple plan - play Rg1, Rg4 and Rf4 and break through on f7. The only thing Black can really do to stop this plan is play ..f6, but that in turn will open the center/kingside favorably for White. All in all, White is close to winning already. }
*

