[White "The Caveman: 4... h6"]
[Black "77. The Caveman 4... h6 5. g4 Bd7 and 6... h5 7. gxh5 Nh6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bd7 6. Nc3 h5 7. gxh5 Nh6 8. Bg5
{ The pin on the e7-pawn is quite annoying for Black. } 8... Bg4 9. Be2
{ White should not let go of the h5-pawn easily. } 9... Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Qd7 11.
Bxh6 { Castling long is also fine. } 11... Rxh6 12. O-O-O Qf5
{ Now White cannot protect the h5-pawn any longer, but he has made Black waste a lot of time to recover his pawn. }
13. Nf3 Rxh5 14. Kb1
{ Here White has to be careful.  14.Ng5?  allows  14...Rxh4!  15.Rxh4?  Qxg5+. }
14... Rh6 15. Ng5 f6
{ In case of  15...e6  16.Rh3!  followed by Rf3 is hard to deal with for Black. }
16. exf6
{ Here in Terzidaki - Makka  (Porto Rio 2014)   White went for the speculative piece sac  16.f4?!  fxg5  17.fxg5  Rh8  18.e6  and eventually lost. The text seems straightforward to me. }
16... Rxf6 17. f4
{ White is clearly better. he intends Rde1 and Ne6 with a dominant position. Even if Black manages to prevent the knight from coming to e6, his f8-bishop remains a problem piece. }
*

