[White "The Caveman: 4... h6"]
[Black "79. The Caveman 4... h6 5. g4 Bh7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bh7
{ 5...Be4  6.f3  Bh7  has no independent value because White will soon play  f4  anyway.   5...Bg6?!  6.h5  Bh7  only helps White because he would rather his h-pawn be on  h5  than on  h4. }
6. e6 { The typical Caveman sacrifice! } 6... fxe6 7. Bd3
{ White should quickly start focusing on the weakened light squares. } 7...
Bxd3 { If Black doesn't take then Bxh7 Rxh7 Qd3 will amount to much the same. }
8. Qxd3 Qd6 { Preparing ...e5. } 9. f4
{ Of course we should not allow ...e5!  Newcomers to this variation may be tempted by the move   9.Qg6+ ?  Kd8  ,  when Black is deprived of his castling rights. But after  10.f4  the freeing move  10...e5 !  has become possible because White's queen is attacked, and  11.Qxd6+  exd6  12.fxe5  dxe5  13.dxe5  Nd7  is probably a slightly worse endgame for White. }
9... Nd7 10. Nf3 O-O-O 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. fxe5 Qc7 13. Nc3
{ Black's f8-bishop and g8-knight are permanently stuck! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: 4... h6"]
[Black "80. The Caveman 4... h6 5. g4 Bh7 6. e6 Qd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bh7 6. e6 Qd6
{ This is Black's main alternative to ...fxe6, intending Qxe6+. There is also   6...Nf6  ,  but that move doesn't solve the issue of how to deal with the e6-pawn, which prevents Black from deploying the Bf8 and Rh8.  See the model game Maxime Vachier-Lagrave vs. Ding Liren for an example of 6... Nf6. }
7. exf7+ { We misplace Black's king instead. } 7... Kxf7 8. f4
{ Black's second idea with ...Qd6 is to prepare ..e5, which this move decisively prevents. }
8... Qe6+ { This is a bit greedy. } 9. Be2 Qe4 10. Nf3 Qxc2 11. Ne5+ Ke8 12. g5
{ Threatening Bh5+. } 12... Qxd1+ { 12...Qe4  13.Rh2!  doesn't help Black. }
13. Bxd1 Nd7 { 13...g6  14.h5! } 14. g6 Nxe5 15. gxh7 Nd3+ 16. Kd2
{ White wins a piece. } *

