[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: Odds and Ends"]
[Black "84. The Caveman: 6... Nh6!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Nh6
{ This is quite an interesting move. Black can still choose to take at b2 at some point, but he can also exchange on d3, or simply play ...e6 and ...c5. So White now has to make moves that are good against all those options! }
7. Ne2
{ 7.Bxh6?!  Bxd3  8.Qxd3  Rxh6  doesn't promise White anything.   7.Nc3?!  is a favorite of my engine, but I think it prematurely blocks the c2-pawn.   7.Nf3!?  is a fully viable alternative, however. The point here is that White develops his g1-knight and castles kingside pretty much regardless of what Black does, so we can make those moves while Black has to answer the question how he is going to resolve the situation with his f5-bishop and h6-knight. }
7... Bxd3
{ 7...Qxb2  8.Nbc3!  Bxd3  9.cxd3  Qa3  otherwise Rb1 followed by Rxb7 will give White great play.  10.Rb1  b6  11.O-O   11.e6!?  is an interesting alternative in the spirit of the Caveman.  e6  12.Rb3  Qa5  13.Ng3  g6  14.Qc2   14.Bf6  is another idea  Nd7  15.Rc1  and White is threatening, for example, Nb5 and Nce4.   7...e6  8.O-O  Nd7  9.a4!?  and it is not obvious how Black finishes his development, considering the f8-bishop has no good squares. }
8. Qxd3 Qxb2 9. O-O Qxa1 10. Qb3 Nd7 11. e6 fxe6 12. Nd2 Qxf1+ 13. Kxf1
{ With a typical Caveman Accepted position - Black is up material, but has numerous weaknesses and no clear way to finish his development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: Odds and Ends"]
[Black "85. The Caveman: 5... f6!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 f6
{ This is a very interesting possibility which until now hasn't been tried yet in high level games. And I have to be honest: I have no clue how White should get an advantage after this move. If I had the black side of the Caveman I would probably go for this variation! }
6. Bd3
{ 6.Bf4  Qb6!  and   6.Be3  Qb6!  both seem fine for Black. The text is a piece sacrifice that aims to exploit the holes that ..f6 has created. }
6... Bxd3
{ 6...Qd7  7.Bf4  seems a bit better for White. Black's queen is poorly positioned on  d7. }
7. Qxd3 fxg5 8. Qg6+ Kd7 9. e6+ Kc7
{ 9...Kc8  10.hxg5  is also very much possible , but Black should not try  10...Qb6?!  11.Ne2  Qxb2  12.Qe8+  Kc7  13.Qxf8  Qxa1  14.O-O.  White will take on  g7  and restore material balance with a better position. }
10. hxg5
{ This is the starting position of this line. White has a bind on Black's kingside, but he lacks active play for his own pieces. It will take time to bring the knights and rooks into play. Meanwhile, at some point Black will play a knight to f6, after which White is forced to take gxf6 - material equality  (and likely also positional equality)  will be restored that way. Also, the pawn on e6 is often more a weakness than a bone in Black's throat in this line.   In any case I have not been able to find a line that leads to a comfortable edge for White. }
10... Qd6
{ This attacks and pins the e6-pawn, preparing moves like ...Nd7 and ...Nf6. }
11. Ne2
{ This is the most flexible development of the knights - pre-emptively blocking a check from Qxe6. }
11... Nd7
{ 11...Na6  is a viable alternative.   11...Nf6  12.gxf6  gxf6  13.Qf5!  Bh6  14.Nbc3  Na6  15.f4  and White will have some advantage if he manages to keep the e6-pawn intact. }
12. Nd2 Ndf6 13. gxf6 Nxf6 14. O-O-O
{ 14.Qf5?!  g6!  15.Qxg6  Rg8  and Black takes over the initiative. } 14...
Qxe6 15. Rde1
{ 15.Qg3+  Qd6  16.Nf4!?  g5!  White's intended Ne6+ is not really much of a threat.  17.Ne6+   17.Qxg5?  Bh6!  and Black wins  Kd7  18.Nc5+  Kc7  19.Ne6+  with a draw. }
15... Qg4 16. Qxg4 Nxg4 17. f3 Nf6 18. Nf4
{ White has compensation for the pawn , but no more than that. For example  18...e6!?  19.Nxe6+  Kd7  20.Nf4  Bd6  with a drawish position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: Odds and Ends"]
[Black "86. The Caveman: 5... Qc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qc7
{ The queen is rather passively placed here. } 6. c4
{ I recommend transposing to this more common 4. h4 line, because Black's queen will be misplaced on c7. }
6... e6 7. Nc3 Ne7 8. Nge2 { This knight is going to g3. } 8... Nd7
{ Black can play  8...dxc4  9.Ng3  b5  , but after  10.a4  b4  11.Nce4  Bxe4  12.Nxe4  we see the problem. In the normal h4-line Black would be able to exert significant pressure on the d4-pawn with 12 ...Nf5. Here that isn't possible because the moves Bg5 for White and ...Qc7 for Black have been inserted. }
9. Ng3 Bg6 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3
{ Black will eventually want to play ...c5, but he will have to move his queen again since after White plays a rook to c1 the queen will be misplaced. White is slightly better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: Odds and Ends"]
[Black "87. The Caveman: 5... Qa5+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qa5+
{ A rare move but not particularly good or bad. } 6. c3
{ White can play in various ways here. The only thing I do not recommend is putting the b1-knight on c3, since Black can then get fine play simply by playing ...e6 and ...c5. }
6... e6 7. Ne2 c5 8. dxc5
{ This type of play is similar to what I recommend against the Botvinnik-Carls 3... c5 system. White intends to give up the e5-pawn and play Nd4, b4, attacking the Bf5 and probing the a4-e8 diagonal with Bb5+. }
8... Qc7 { 8...Bxc5?  9.b4. } 9. b4 Nc6
{ After  9...Qxe5  10.Bf4  Qf6  Black's queenside is vulnerable , for example  11.Na3!?  a6  12.Qa4+  Nd7  13.Nb5! }
10. Bf4 Nge7 11. Nd4 Bxb1 { 11...a6  12.Nd2  and White is slightly better. }
12. Nb5
{ This in-between move was winning in Hansen - Hallerod  (Guernsey 2014)  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caveman: Odds and Ends"]
[Black "88. The Caveman: 4... c5?! and 5... Qc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 c5
{ This move is known as dubious. As we will also see in the chapter on the Botvinnik-Carls variation, the move ...c5 doesn't combine well so early with ...Bf5. }
5. dxc5 Qc7
{ It is important to note that  5...e6?  is not possible yet because of  6.g4!  trapping the f5-bishop. }
6. Nc3 Nc6
{ 6...Qxe5+?!  7.Be3  and White is clearly better with  Nf3  coming next. } 7.
Nf3 Rd8
{ 7...Nxe5?  8.Bf4!  is already losing for Black:  8...Nxf3+  9.Qxf3  Qxc5  10.Bb5+  Bd7  11.Bxd7+  Kxd7  12.Nxd5  And White will follow with Rd1 with a winning attack. }
8. Nb5 Qc8
{ 8...Qb8  9.Nbd4.  The text was game 16 from the Botvinnik - Tal rematch , and now we seek to improve on Tal's play. }
9. c3
{ Tal - Botvinnik, 16th game World Championship match 1961 continued:   9.Nfd4  Bg4  10.f3  Bd7  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Nd4  Qb8  13.Qe2  e6  14.Nb3  Bxc5  15.Nxc5  Qb4+  16.c3  Qxc5  17.Be3  Qa5  18.b4  Qc7  19.Bc5  Ne7  20.h5  h6  21.Bd6  Qb7  22.O-O-O !?  Very risky, but that's vintage Tal!  Ra8  23.g4  a5  24.Qf2  axb4  25.cxb4  c5  26.Bxe7  Kxe7  27.Qxc5+  Ke8  28.Kb2  Rc8  29.Qd4  Ba4  30.Rc1  Rxc1  31.Kxc1  White is again a pawn up, but Black has decent compensation here. The game ended in a draw on the 90th  (!)  move. }
9... e6 10. Be3 { Black has no good way to regain his pawn. } *

