[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Botvinnik-Carls Gambit: 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2!?"]
[Black "94. The Botvinnik-Carls Gambit: 4... Nc6 and 5... Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5
{ This is a respectable gambit that became mainstream when Botvinnik used it in his rematch against Tal in 1961 - albeit with little success  (Botvinnik won the rematch easily, but only scored 1 out of 3 with this move)  . Black keeps his options open as to whether he'll develop the c8-bishop outside his pawn chain, and immediately starts counterplay against White's center. }
4. Ne2
{ This is my recommendation. Not because it is objectively the strongest, but because it avoids lines like 4. dxc5 or 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c4 which require White to know a lot of theory - and even then these lines don't offer a clear path to a small advantage  (as far as I know)  .  4. Ne2 looks a bit strange but it has some good ideas. Firstly, it makes Black's development of his c8-bishop a bit more difficult. If this bishop is played to g4 White could answer f3, and on f5 the bishop can be hit by Ng3. With the knight not blocking his f-pawn White can also quickly play the advance f4-f5, of course after he has castled.  On the other hand the e2-knight blocks the smooth development of the f1-bishop. This is solved by the fact that White almost always plays dxc5 followed by Nd4 next.  To clarify, I do not think 4. Ne2 offers White an advantage  (though in some variations White gets great positions)  , but it takes play off the beaten track of established theory very quickly and offers positions that are quite unbalanced. }
4... Nc6
{ Black can also play  4...cxd4   or  4...e6  though these are rare alternatives - I consider them later in this chapter. }
5. c3
{ This does not just defend the d4-pawn but also prepares dxc5 to then prop up the c5-pawn with by playing b4. It also opens the d1-a4 diagonal for the white queen. }
5... Bf5
{ Black has alternatives at this point in   5...cxd4  ,   5...Bg4   and  5...e6  - this transposes to the line 4...e6.  The text allows White to execute his plan with dxc5 and b4. }
6. dxc5 e6 { 6...Nxe5  is an important alternative. } 7. b4 Nxe5
{ Black's main alternative here is  7...a5.  Instead,   7...Bxb1?!  8.Rxb1  Nxe5  9.Nd4  is similar to the line   7...Nxe5  8.Nd4  Bxb1?!  9.Bb5+  - White has great control over the light squares. }
8. Nd4 Bg6
{ Here Black has three moves - the text,   8...Bxb1?!  ,   and  8...Ne7  which is in my view the strongest. }
9. Bb5+
{ Now that Black's light-squared bishop is outside the pawn chain, the a4-e8 diagonal has become more vulnerable. }
9... Nd7 10. O-O Nf6 11. f4
{ Another disadvantage of having the bishop on g6 - it can be harassed by f4-f5. }
11... Be7 12. f5 exf5 13. Nxf5
{ White will win the bishop pair and achieves a good position after playing normal moves  (Be3 followed by Nd2-f3)  . He can play for a kingside attack, play against the d5-pawn, or try to utilize his pawn mass on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Botvinnik-Carls Gambit: 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2!?"]
[Black "95. The Botvinnik-Carls Gambit: 4... Nc6, 5... Bf5 and 8... Bxb1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2 Nc6 5. c3 Bf5 6. dxc5 e6 7. b4 Nxe5 8. Nd4
Bxb1 9. Bb5+
{ An important in-between move that forces the e5-knight back to the sub-optimal d7-square. }
9... Nd7 10. Rxb1
{ With Black's light-squared bishop gone, White has uncontested control over the a4-e8 diagonal. The c5-pawn hampers Black's development and Black must continually deal with the consequences of a possible c5-c6 push. }
10... Nf6 11. O-O Be7
{ In case of   11...g6 ?!  12.Bg5 !  Bg7  13.Qf3  - White will play Bxd7 next after which Black is forced to retake with his king, otherwise he loses a piece on f6. }
12. c4
{ There are various ways to proceed, but this seems the most promising to me. White immediately starts chipping away at the black center. }
12... a6
{ 12...O-O  is answered by  13.c6!  bxc6  14.Nxc6  Qe8  15.Ne5  and Black has significant problems to solve. }
13. Ba4 dxc4 14. c6 bxc6 15. Bf4
{ Before retaking on c6 White first takes away the c7-square from the black queen. }
15... Nd5
{ Black has a lot of possible moves but none of them seem any good:   15...Qc8  16.Nxc6  Nd5  17.Ne5  probably transposes to the main line.   15...e5?!  16.Nxc6  Qc7  17.Nxe5  and White wins.   15...Rc8  16.Nxc6  Qb6  17.Ne5  and White should win.   15...Qb6  16.Nxc6  Nd5  17.Ne5  and White wins again.   15...Nb6  16.Bxc6+  and White wins the exchange. }
16. Nxc6 Qc8 17. Ne5 O-O 18. Bxd7 Qc7
{ Because the f4-bishop is hanging Black will regain some material. } 19. Bg3
Bd6 20. Nxf7 Bxg3 21. Bxe6 Bxh2+ 22. Kh1 Nf4 23. Ng5+ Nxe6 24. Nxe6
{ After the dust of all the tactics has settled, White is again winning an exchange. }
*

