1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2 Nc6 5. c3 Bf5 6. dxc5 e6 7. b4 Nxe5 8. Nd4
Ne7 { This seems the most solid of Black's options. } 9. Bb5+ N5c6 10. O-O
{ We now follow a simple plan: Play Nd2, pile up on the e-file and try to make use of the f5-bishop's precarious position. The e7-knight keeps Black's position together, but at the same time it blocks him from finishing development. If the e7-knight moves, White should take the f5-bishop to open the e-file. If Black plays ...a6, again White should take on c6 and continue his plan. }
10... Qd7 11. Nd2 a6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Re1
