[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2 Nc6 5. c3 cxd4
{ Not at all a bad move, though it makes White's play fairly simple. } 6. cxd4
Bf5 7. Nbc3 e6 8. Ng3
{ In similar positions with the white knight on f3 Black's task is considerably easier, since he can always play ...Bg4 to exchange on f3 and keep a super solid position. He has no weaknesses and can pile up on the d4-pawn, while White's bishop pair won't matter in a position like this. Nor can White as easily advance his pawns on the kingside. }
8... Bg6 9. Be3 { A useful prophylactic move guarding the d4-pawn. } 9... Nge7
{ Now Black would like to play Nc8-b6, Be7, O-O and Rc8 and play on the queenside. }
10. h4 { Probing for weaknesses. } 10... h6
{ 10...h5  is actually the more common reply to  h4  in the Advance variation , but here it doesn't gel well with the slow plan of Nc8-b6 and so on. }
11. h5 Bh7 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3
{ This is Vachier-Lagrave - Jerez Perez  (2012)  . White can castle short and prepare an attack with f4-f5, which he eventually executed successfully. }
*

