[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2 Nc6 5. c3 Bg4
{ This move is surprisingly hard to meet.   My first inclination was to play  6.f3  , but after  6...Bf5  we have similar positions as in the  5...Bf5  line except White has weakened the e1-h4 diagonal , which is crucial in some lines  (Black will play ...a5, ...axb4 and ...Qh4+ picking up the b4-pawn)  (.)   6.dxc5  is also not as attractive , because after  6...Nxe5  White cannot continue with  7.Nd4  because his knight is pinned. }
6. h3
{ This is not very ambitious, but it won't lead you into trouble either. } 6...
Bxe2
{ If  6...Bf5  then we have the same position as after  5...Bf5  except with  h3  inserted , which is 95% of the time quite useful for White. }
7. Bxe2 e6
{ Now the position is pretty dry - the bishop pair means little with this closed pawn structure, and Black has no real weaknesses to attack  (yet)  . }
8. O-O Qb6
{ Black can also exchange on d4, but that allows White to develop his pieces more harmoniously - knight to c3, bishop to e3 and d3, queen to d2, and so on. }
9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b4 Be7 11. Be3 Qc7 12. f4 Nh6 13. Nd2
{ Vachier-Lagrave - Anand , 2017 continued with  13.Na3. } 13... Nf5 14. Bf2
O-O 15. Nf3 { White is threatening g4. } 15... h5 16. Bd3 g6 17. Bxf5 gxf5 18.
Ne1
{ Black cannot really defend the h-pawn, but is it good for White to open lines in front of his king? You decide. }
