[White "The Botvinnik-Carls Gambit: 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2!?"]
[Black "103. The Botvinnik-Carls Gambit: 4... cxd4 and 6... e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Nc3 e6
{ 6...a6  7.f4  should be similar. } 7. f4
{ Now the line resembles a classical/Steinitz French defense 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5. The main differences are that 1  here it is Black to move, and 2  Black's g8-knight is on d7 in that variation. These factors should even out as Black will have to spend one or more moves to deploy the g8-knight, but it makes play a bit different. Black can contain the kingside better by putting the knight on e7 or even h6, but at the same time he has less control over the squares on the queenside. }
7... Qb6 8. Be3 Bd7
{ In the similar line in the French , Black often plays  ...Bc5  but this isn't so good here:  8...Bc5  9.Bb5!  Bd7  10.Na4!  Qa5+  11.Bd2  Bb4  12.c3  Be7  and now White has a pleasant choice between the aggressive  13.f5  , exploiting Black's lack of kingside development   and  13.b4  , increasing control over the queenside.   Note that  8...Qxb2?  isn't possible because of  9.Ncb5!  Kd8  10.a3!  and Black's queen will be trapped with either 11. Rb1 or 11. Nxc6+ bxc6 12. Bd4. }
9. Qd2 Nxd4
{ White was threatening Nxe6.   9...Bc5?  10.Na4!  doesn't work out for Black. }
10. Bxd4 Bc5 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Bd3
{ Or  12.Qf2  +=.  White has a slight advantage. He can still decide whether to castle queenside or to go for a pleasant endgame  (since he will control the d4-square)  with Qf2, offering the exchange of queens. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Botvinnik-Carls Gambit: 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2!?"]
[Black "104. The Botvinnik-Carls Gambit: 4... e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2 e6
{ This rare move basically transposes to an Advance French Defense - 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 - except White has a move extra - though that move was used for Ng1-e2, perhaps not the most ideal move. }
5. c3 Nc6 6. g3
{ White should adapt to the situation. In the French Advance this idea  (g3 and then Bh3)  is quite common, but with the knight already on e2 blocking any other development of the f1-bishop White doesn't have much choice anyway!  It should be said that in general when the center is closed like it is here, it is less important to know concrete lines and more important to know ideas. White will want to control the kingside as much as possible and eventually organize an attack over the f-file. Black's focus is the queenside, and eventually coming through on the c-, b- or even a-file. }
6... Qb6 7. Bh3 Bd7 8. O-O a5 9. a4 Nh6 10. Bxh6 gxh6 11. Na3 O-O-O 12. Nb5
{ This is the game Shirov - Ghaem Maghami  (2017)  , in which White eventually scored a nice win. }
