[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Supi, Luis Paulo vs. Van Riemsdijk, Dirk Dagobert"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2 8. e6
Qxa1 9. Qb3 Qxd4 10. Qxb7 Qe5+ 11. Be3
{ One should remember that in this variation the bishop belongs on e3, in order to go to a7 to attack the b8-knight. }
11... fxe6
{ White was threatening  Qc8+.  For example:  11...Qd6?  12.Qc8+  Qd8  13.exf7+  and White wins the queen. }
12. Qxa8
{ Better is  12.Nf3!  first, because then Black's queen can't go to c7.  Qd6  13.Qxa8  Nf6  14.Bxa7  Nfd7  15.Qb7!  and Black can't untangle his knights. Moreover , White is threatening  Qc8+  followed by  Ng5+. }
12... Nf6 13. Nf3 Qc7 14. Bxa7 { 14.O-O  Nfd7  15.Bxa7  is the same. } 14...
Nd7 15. O-O e5
{ 15...c5!  would have put up more resistance. Black is threatening to untangle with ...Qc6. He is still in a difficult spot, but not yet lost. This is by the way why earlier on, 12. Nf3 was preferable over 12. Qxa8. }
16. Nbd2
{ White's plan is simple - put the rook on the b-file, play a knight to g5 and watch Black's position crumble. }
16... e6 17. Rb1
{ 17.Ng5  first is better - the e6-pawn cannot really be covered. } 17... Bd6
18. Bxb8 Nxb8
{ Black's final chance was  18...Qc8!  pinning the b8-bishop  19.Ng5  Bxb8  20.Nxe6  Kf7  and he seems to be holding on. }
19. Ng5 O-O { 19...Qc8  20.Rb7!  is decisive. } 20. Nxe6 Qf7 21. Nxf8
{ White is up an exchange and can continue with Nf3-g5 or c4 while Black lacks counterplay. }
