[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Beckemeier, Werner vs. Johann, Stefan"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2 8. e6
fxe6 9. Nf3
{ Since Black is waiting with capturing on a1, White simply develops  (and already protects the d4-pawn so that after Qxa1 Qb3 Black's queen will be trapped)  , intending to castle short next. }
9... Nd7 10. O-O Qxa1
{ Black finally relents, but his waiting moves haven't really helped. } 11. Qb3
{ White will follow up with Nbd2 when the 'rook sacrifice' is really more an exchange of Black's queen for two rooks and two pawns. }
11... b5 12. Nbd2
{ 12.Nc3  is superficially a mistake, since on c3 the knight has no good squares to go to and it blocks White's queen from going to e3, but White can follow up powerfully with Ne2-f4. }
12... Qxf1+ 13. Kxf1
{ Materially Black is well ahead, but his position is riddled with weaknesses and nearly impossible to salvage. Meanwhile White simply has to put his pieces in the right position and he can reap the benefits of 8. e6! }
13... Nh6 14. Qe3
{ Also strong is  14.Qc3!?  Rc8  15.Qe3  e5  16.dxe5  when the queen is eyeing the a7-pawn. }
14... e5 15. Nxe5
{ 15.dxe5  is also good , but after the text White exchanges an important defender  (and arguably Black's only active piece)  (.) }
15... Nxe5 16. Qxe5 Kd7 { This  (temporarily)  prevents Qc7 and Qe6. } 17. Nf3
{ Stronger was  17.Nb3  intending Nc5+ with a winning attack. } 17... Ng4 18.
Qf5+ Kc7 19. Bf4+ Kb6 20. Qe6 Rd8 21. Nd2
{ Also strong seems  21.Ne1!  followed by Nd3 and Nc5. } 21... g6 22. Nb3 Bh6
23. Bxh6 Nxh6 24. Qxe7 Nf5
{ Finally Black has more or less completed his development, but it is just too late! White now starts a decisive attack on Black's king. }
25. Qc5+ Kb7 26. Na5+ Ka6 27. Nxc6 Rd7 28. Nb4+ Kb7
{ 28...Ka5  29.Nxd5  and Black has nothing better than  29...Rxd5  30.Qxd5  when the endgame should be an easy win for White. }
29. Qc6+ { Black resigned because of  29...Kb8  30.Na6#. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Charochkina, Daria vs. Arabidze, Meri"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxb2 7. Bxf5 Qxa1 8. e6
{ This move is of paramount importance - it weakens the light squares on Black's kingside  (e6, f7, g6)  and prevents Black from smoothly developing. }
8... fxe6 { One of various possible answers. } 9. Bg6+
{ 9.Bxe6!?  is also interesting , for example:  9...Na6  10.Nf3  Nc7  11.Bh3!  Nf6  12.O-O  with good compensation for the sacrificed material. }
9... Kd8 10. Nf3 Nd7 11. Bf4
{ White wants to stop the freeing advance  ...e5  , but this merely encourages it. In the theory section I recommend  11.O-O  , after which  11...e5  can be answered with either  12.c4   or  12.Qd2  (with ideas of trapping Black's queen.) }
11... e5 12. dxe5 e6
{ Now Black can in theory bring out the f8-bishop and g8-knight via e7, though in practice she still has a lot of problems to solve. }
13. O-O Be7 { This does not make much sense.  13...Ne7  is a better try. } 14.
Bf7 { White is right to focus on e6 as the main weakness in Black's camp. }
14... Nf8
{ This was probably the idea behind 13... Be7, but Black is mistaken if she thinks she can defend the e6-pawn adequately. She should instead be looking for a way to give up the pawn in a favorable manner. }
15. Nd4 Kd7 16. Qd3
{ Threatening not just 17. Qh3 but also 17. Nc3 Qb2 18. Rb1. } 16... Qxa2 17.
Qh3 { Also strong is  17.Bxe6+  Nxe6  18.Qh3  with a strong initiative. } 17...
Qc4 18. Nxe6 Nxe6 19. Qxe6+ Kd8 20. g3
{ This quiet move, simply defending the f4-bishop, shows the basic problem with Black's position in the Caveman gambit. None of her pieces are participating and she has no good way to defend herself, even though she is  (still)  ahead a pawn and an exchange! }
20... Nh6 { 20...Rh6!?  was a better try. } 21. Bxh5
{ 21.Nd2!  wins. Black's queen has to stay on the a3-f8 diagonal protecting the e7-bishop, because otherwise White plays the winning Bg5.  Qc5   21...Qb4  22.Rb1  Qc5  23.Rxb7  22.Nb3  Qb4  23.Bxh5. }
21... Rc8
{ Perhaps  21...Qxc2  intending 22  ...Qf5  would give Black drawing chances. }
22. Nd2 { Now White spots the winning idea. } 22... Qc5 23. Nb3 Qb6 24. Qg6
{ Or  24.Bg5!  with the decisive threat of Qd6#. } 24... Rf8 25. Bd2
{ Again ,  25.Bg5! } 25... Qa6 26. Bg5
{ Again, White spots the winning idea a move later. } 26... Nf5 27. Bxe7+ Kxe7
{ 27...Nxe7  28.Qd6#. } 28. Qg5+
{ White wins Black's queen after  28...Kd7  29.Nc5+. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
