[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hinrichs, Lars vs. Powierski, Emil"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4
{ This move is more dangerous than 6... Qxb2 or 6... Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qxb2. } 7.
Nf3 Qxb2 8. Bxf5 Qxa1 9. e6
{ As usual, this move is critical - it makes the development of Black's kingside difficult and highlights the weak light squares. }
9... fxe6 10. Bg6+
{ In the theory section I recommend   10.Bxe6.  With White not having a pawn on d4 it can be hard to get through Black's pawn mass in the center. }
10... Kd8 11. Nd4 Kc8 12. O-O e5
{ This weakens Black's pawn center as well as give White possibilities on the c8-h3 diagonal. Black should just develop with ...Nd7 and ...Ngf6 when White still has to prove his compensation. }
13. Bf5+ { White immediately pounces on the opportunity. } 13... Nd7
{ This knight is in an unfortunate pin , but  13...Kc7?  14.Ne6+  would simply drop the f8-bishop. }
14. Nb3 Qxa2 15. c4 { Thus Black's pawn center is torn apart. } 15... e6
{ After  15...d4  the piece sac  16.Nxd4!  is crude but effective.  16...Ngf6  17.Nb5!  (threatening Bxf6)  Rh7  18.Qd3!  and White has a winning attack. }
16. Bxe6 Bd6
{ After this move Black is clearly lost. But after  16...Ngf6  17.cxd5  Qa6  18.Bxf6  gxf6  19.Qf3!  he is also under heavy pressure  (with dxc6 and Qxf6 to follow)  . }
17. cxd5 c5
{ Keeping the c-file temporarily closed, but the light squares are becoming increasingly weak. }
18. Nc3 Qa3 19. Qc2
{ 19.Nb5  Qa6  20.Qd3!  Ngf6  21.Bxf6  Is also winning. After  gxf6  22.Bxd7+  Kxd7  23.Qf5+  White's queen will enter on either e6 or f6 with check. }
19... Nf6 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Nb5 Qa6 22. Nxc5 { Or  22.Nxd6+  Qxd6  23.Nxc5! }
22... Qxb5 23. Bxd7+ Qxd7 24. Nxd7+ Kxd7 25. Qf5+
{ White's queen enters on e6 while the rook will join the attack decisively via c1. Therefore, Black resigned. }
