[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Barbosa, Evandro Amorim vs. Molina, Roberto Junio Brito"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qg4
{ Black is content with an extra pawn. } 8. Bxf5
{ This is preferable to 8. O-O as on g4 Black's queen has a lot of options on the 4th rank. }
8... Qxf5 9. O-O { My recommendation is to play 9. c4 immediately. } 9... Qd7
{ An interesting decision. Retreating the queen behind his own pawns means Black has more defensive resources, but it also means his position becomes more passive and cramped. }
10. c4 e6 11. Nc3 Ne7 12. Qe2 { Vacating the d1-square for a rook. } 12... Nf5
13. Rfd1 Bb4
{ 13...d4!?  14.Ne4  c5  seems a good try for Black , but perhaps he was afraid of  15.b4!  when white has good compensation for the pawn. }
14. Rac1 { 14.Ne4!?  was an interesting alternative. } 14... Na6
{ It is difficult for Black to consider castling kingside , since his pawn structure there is already compromised. Take for example the line  14...O-O  15.Nd4  Nxd4  16.Rxd4  c5  17.Rd3  d4?  18.Bf6!  and White has a winning attack. }
15. Ne4 Be7
{ Again  15...O-O  16.Nf6+!  gxf6  17.Bxf6  is a promising piece sacrifice. White can continue with Ng5, Rc3 and/or Rd3 - the attack plays itself. }
16. cxd5 exd5
{ Black's first notable inaccuracy.  16...cxd5  is solid , although White retains decent compensation after  17.Nd4  Nxd4  18.Rxd4. }
17. Nf6+
{ Black must have underestimated this move. The e-file is now opened up favorably for White. }
17... gxf6 18. exf6 Qe6 19. Qf1
{ Stronger is  19.Qc2!  which prevents Black's next move. } 19... Nc5
{ This throws a spanner in the works on e4. } 20. fxe7 Ne4 21. Nd4 Nxd4 22.
Rxd4
{ Material is now equal. White is somewhat better as Black's king is unsafe and the e7-pawn is a threat, while Black has no good way  (yet)  to get rid of it. }
22... Qe5
{ Still ,  22...Nxg5  23.hxg5  Qd6!  seems fairly solid for Black. He can use the e7-pawn as a shield for his own king and try to activate his own rooks next. }
23. Rb4
{ 23.Rxd5!!  Qxd5   23...cxd5??  24.Qb5#  24.Rd1!  and White wins Black's queen for two rooks due to the threat on  d8.  Play might continue  24...Nxg5  25.Rxd5  Nf3+  26.gxf3  cxd5  27.Qb5+  and White's queen is far superior to the two rooks here. }
23... f6
{ 23...Rb8?  24.f4!  Qd6  25.Rxe4!  dxe4  26.Rd1  isn't possible for Black.   However , again  23...Nxg5!  24.hxg5  Rb8  and Black has a difficult but sturdy position. After the text Black falls victim to a series of tactics. }
24. Rxb7 Nd6
{ It turns out that after  24...fxg5  25.Rxc6!  White has a decisive attack, the threats are Qb5 and Qa6. In fact the computer already announces mate in 15! }
25. Re1
{ This works , but why not  25.Rxc6!  Nxb7   25...fxg5  26.Rxd6!  followed by Qb5+.  26.Bxf6!  For the next 8 moves or so White retains a winning position but often misses an easier/faster win. }
25... Qf5 26. Rc7 fxg5 27. Rxc6
{ 27.Qa6!  was more accurate here, when Black cannot really prevent Qxc6+. }
27... Nc4 28. b3 Nb6 29. hxg5 Qxg5 30. Rc7
{ 30.Qb5!  Kf7  31.Rc3  with a decisive attack. } 30... d4 31. f4 Qd5 32. Re5
Qd6 33. Qb5+ Nd7 34. Qb7
{ White has finally decisively penetrated Black's defensive lines. } 34... Nb6
{ This leads to a nice finish. } 35. Qxa8+ Nxa8 36. Rc8+ Kf7 37. Rxh8 Nc7 38.
Rf8+
{ Without this move White wouldn't be winning. The king has to be chased away from the e8-square! }
38... Kg7 39. Rc8 { Black has no way to prevent the e7-pawn from promoting. } *

