[Black "Katz, Alexander R vs. Koons, Nat"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Qxd4 7. Nf3 Qg4 8. O-O
e6 9. Bxf5 Qxf5 10. c4
{ We've reached our preferred setup via an alternative move order. } 10... Ne7
11. cxd5
{ This is a bit early. Now if  11...cxd5  Black can develop his b8-knight to c6.   11.Qb3!  b6  12.Nc3  Nd7  13.cxd5   13.Rad1  is a viable option too  Nc5  14.Qa3!  exd5  15.b4  Ne6  16.Qa4!?  and White can develop strong pressure on the c- and d-files. }
11... Nxd5
{ This is also an option, but it does decrease Black's control over the c4- and e4-squares as well as introduce tactical ideas on the open d-file. In return, Black's kingside development becomes a lot easier. }
12. Nc3 Bc5 { 12...Nxc3??  13.Qd8#  - an example of d-file tactics. } 13. Qb3
b6 14. Nxd5 { 14.Rfe1  O-O  15.Qa4  makes Black's life more difficult. } 14...
exd5
{ 14...cxd5?  15.Qa4+  Nd7  16.b4!  Be7  17.Nd4!  and White has a dangerous initiative. }
15. Qc3 a5 { White was threatening b4, trapping the c5-bishop. } 16. a3 a4
{ Now White is out of threats. } 17. Nd4 Qg4 18. Rad1 O-O
{ White has no compensation for the pawn. } 19. Rfe1 Ra7 20. Rd3 Bxd4 21. Rxd4
Qe6 22. Rd3 Nd7 23. Rg3 Re8 { White has no real threats on the kingside. } 24.
Rge3 c5
{ Black has developed and defended adequately, and now that White is out of activity Black can finally put his queenside pawn majority in motion. }
25. Qc2 d4 26. Re4 Qf5 27. Qe2 Rxe5
{ This leads to a favorable endgame for Black , but he could have played more patiently with  27...Re6! }
28. Rxe5 Nxe5 29. Qxe5 Qxe5 30. Rxe5 f6
{ This is Black's point - he regains the piece. } 31. Re6
{ 31.Bxf6!  gxf6  32.Re6  was definitely a better try , though Black is still by all means a pawn up. }
31... fxg5 32. hxg5 b5 33. Kf1 Kf7 34. Rc6 c4 35. g6+ Ke7 36. Rc5
{ White cannot afford to be distracted by the h5-pawn.  36.Ke2  Rd7  37.g3  Rd5  38.Kd2  and the game is not yet decided. }
36... Rb7 37. Rxh5 b4 { Black is breaking through. The rest is easy. } 38. Rh4
c3 39. Re4+ Kf6 40. bxc3 b3 41. Rf4+ Kxg6 42. Rg4+ Kf5 43. Rxd4 b2
{ This pawn will promote as soon as White runs out of checks. } 44. g4+ Kg6 45.
Rd6+ Kf7 46. Rd7+ Rxd7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
