[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nepomniachtchi, Ian vs. Miton, Kamil"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bg5 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nd2
Ne7 9. Ngf3 Qa6 10. c4
{ Allowing the exchange of queens would go against the nature of the opening, but also the nature of the position. With both queens and the light-squared bishops gone, Black would have excellent control over important squares like e4 and f5. }
10... Nf5 11. O-O Bb4 12. b3
{ Since Black is not threatening ...Bxd2 or ...Qxc4, this move is perhaps unnecessary. But it can be a useful option to be able to retake with a pawn should Black play ...dxc4. }
12... Nd7 13. Rfc1
{ White pre-emptively puts his rook on the c-file, as this file is the most likely to be opened  (after cxd5 cxd5)  . At the same time he makes space for the d2-knight to be rerouted via f1, as this knight is not doing much at the moment. }
13... O-O 14. Nf1 Rfe8
{ 14...c5  is more active , though perhaps Black did not like the complications that arise after  15.a3  Ba5  16.b4!   Barring that ,  14...Ba3!  15.Rc2  c5!  seems to give Black good chances. This game shows that without the  ...c5  advance , Black's position is too passive in this variation. }
15. Ne3
{ White intends to exchange the f5-knight after which Black's king does not have a lot of defenders around himself. }
15... g6 16. Qc2 { Calmly unpinning the c4-pawn. } 16... Ba3 17. Rd1 Rac8 18.
Nxf5 exf5 19. Bh6 Nf8
{ This is too passive. Stronger is  19...dxc4  20.bxc4  Nb6!  21.c5  Nd5  and Black has a decent position, despite the odd-looking position of his bishop on a3. }
20. c5 Ne6 21. Rdb1 { Preparing a queenside advance. } 21... Bb4 22. a3 Ba5 23.
b4 Bd8
{ Evacuated just in time! However, White now has a strong initiative on both sides of the board. }
24. a4 b6 25. Qd2 Qb7 26. Bg5 Be7 27. Bf6
{ This is committal , but in the end it turns out well.  27.cxb6!  axb6  28.a5!  and White keeps all his trump cards. }
27... Rb8
{ This loses immediately.   27...Bxf6!  28.exf6  Qc7!  was necessary , when  29.cxb6  axb6  30.a5  Qd8  31.a6  Qxf6  sees White obtain good compensation for the pawn. }
28. Qh6
{ After  28...Bxf6  29.exf6  Black is too late to prevent Ng5 with a decisive attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Balogh, Csaba vs. Tari, Aryan"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 Qb6 8. Nd2
c5 9. c4 Nc6 { 9...Qxb2  is the most dangerous option here. } 10. Ngf3 cxd4 11.
O-O
{ My recommendation is to take  11.cxd5  Nb4   11...exd5  12.O-O  and Black has to reckon with both e6! and Nb3xd4  12.Qb3  Nxd5  13.Qa4+  Qc6  14.Qxc6+  bxc6  15.Nxd4  and White has a better endgame. }
11... Nge7 { Now Black can retake with the e7-knight should White play cxd5. }
12. a3 { White intends to grab space with b4. } 12... Qxb2
{ 12...a5!  seems equal. } 13. Rfc1
{ Threatening to trap the queen with Rab1 Qa2 Rc2. } 13... Qb6 14. Rab1
{ 14.cxd5!  Nxd5   14...exd5?!  15.Nb3  and Black cannot really move the e7-knight because of the reply e6!  15.Rab1  Qc7  16.Nxd4  and White has excellent compensation for the pawn. }
14... Qa6 { Now the c4-pawn is pinned, which hampers White's initiative. } 15.
Qb3 Rb8 16. Bxe7
{ This is the only way to make something of the central tension, since otherwise Black simply recaptures on d5 with the e7-knight. However, now Black will be able to castle after which his development problems are over. }
16... Bxe7 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Qxd5 O-O
{ The position is about equal here - White has compensation for his pawn, but not more than that. }
19. e6 { This seems the only way to make the position more interesting. } 19...
f5
{ 19...fxe6?  20.Qxe6+  Kh8   20...Rf7  21.Rxc6!  Qxc6  22.Qxc6  bxc6  23.Rxb8+  21.Rxc6  Qxc6  22.Qxe7  obviously isn't what Black wants.   19...Qxa3?  20.Rxc6!  Rbd8!   20...bxc6?  21.exf7+  Rxf7  22.Rxb8+  and White wins  21.exf7+  Rxf7  22.Qe6  bxc6  23.Ne5  Rf8  24.Nxf7  Rxf7  25.Ne4!  and White is winning. }
20. Qd7 Qxa3 21. Nc4
{ Black is two pawns up, but White has good compensation in the form of Black's weakened kingside and the passed e6-pawn. }
21... Qc5 22. Nb6 Qa3
{ Black shows that he would be fine with a draw by repetition. } 23. Nd5
{ White however wants more! } 23... Rbd8 24. Qxb7 Rxd5 25. Rxc6
{ White is better. He has regained one of his sacrificed pawns without losing any of his positional advantages. }
25... Rdd8 26. Rc7
{ 26.Ne5  a5  27.Nd7  Re8  28.Qb5!  , targeting the f5-pawn , was a strong alternative. }
26... Rfe8 { 26...Rb8  immediately was necessary. } 27. Ne5
{ Threatening Nc6. } 27... Rb8
{ Black finds the right idea, but a move too late! } 28. Qxb8 Rxb8 29. Rxb8+
Kh7 30. Rcc8 { Threatening Rh8#. } 30... Bd8 31. g4
{ Not  31.Rxd8?  Qc1+  32.Kh2  Qf4+  33.Kg1  when Black can choose between a repetition of moves , or trying for more with  33...Qxe5.   However , winning would have been  31.Kh2!  (A strong prophylactic move against various checks by Black's queen)  Qa5  32.Nd3!  Bxh4  33.Nf4!  and Black has no more counterplay. }
31... d3
{ Not just bringing the pawn one step closer to promotion, but also opening the a1-h8 diagonal for the queen. }
32. Rxd8 Qa1+ 33. Kg2 Qxe5
{ A very complicated endgame arises. Both sides have a passed pawn on the 6th rank, but it is hard to make progress with both kings being liable to continuous checks. }
34. Rh8+ Kg6 35. gxh5+ Kf6 36. Rhf8+ Ke7
{ 36...Kxe6??  37.Rbe8+  and White wins. } 37. Rfe8+ Kf6 38. Rf8+ Ke7 39. Rf7+
Kd6 40. Rd8+ Kc5 41. Rxd3 Qe4+ 42. Rf3 Qg4+ 43. Rg3 Qe4+ 44. Kh2 Qxh4+ 45. Kg1
Qxh5 46. Rxa7
{ The position has simplified a little, but the verdict is still: draw. } 46...
Qd1+ 47. Kg2 Qd5+ 48. Rf3 Qxe6 49. Rxg7
{ Now the position has become even simpler. To be clear, only White is playing for a win here. If he finds a way to win Black's f5-pawn, or find a favorable way to trade his rooks for the queen, he might be able to win the game. }
49... Qf6 50. Ra7 Qg6+ 51. Kf1 Kd4 52. Ra4+ Kd5 53. Rd3+ Kc5 54. Rf4 Qf6 55.
Rdf3 Qa1+ 56. Kg2 Qg7+ 57. Rg3 Qf6 58. Rff3 Kd4 59. Rc3 f4 60. Rgd3+ Ke4 61.
f3+ Kf5 62. Rc5+ Kg6 63. Rdc3 Qd4 64. Rc6+ Kg7 65. Rc2 Kf7 66. Rc7+ Kf6 67.
R2c4 Qd2+ 68. Kh3 Kg5 69. R7c5+ Kg6 70. Rc6+ Kg7 71. Rc7+ Kg6 72. R4c6+ Kg5 73.
Rc5+ Kg6 74. R7c6+ Kg7 75. Kg4 Qg2+ 76. Kxf4
{ White has managed to win the pawn. The question now becomes: can he avoid all of the checks and at the same time get his pawn to the 8th rank? Tablebase says the position is drawn. }
76... Qh2+ 77. Ke3 Qg1+ 78. Ke4 Qe1+ 79. Kf5 Qb1+ 80. Kf4 Qb4+ 81. Kf5 Qb1+ 82.
Rc2 Qb5+ 83. Kg4 Qb4+ 84. R6c4 Qe1 85. Rc7+ Kg8
{ Black must remain careful:  85...Kf6??  86.R2c6+  Ke5  87.Re7+  and White wins. }
86. Kf5 Qb1 87. f4 Qb5+ 88. Kg4 Qd5 89. R2c5 Qg2+ 90. Kf5 Qh3+ 91. Kf6 Qh6+ 92.
Ke5 Qh8+ 93. Kd5 Qh1+ 94. Kd4 Qa1+ 95. Rc3 Qa4+ 96. Ke3 Qe8+ 97. Kf2 Qe4 98.
R7c4 Qd5 99. Kg3 Qd1 100. f5 Kf7 101. Rc7+ Kf6 102. R7c6+ Kg5
{ 102...Kxf5??  103.R3c5+  Ke4  104.Re6+  Kd4  105.Rd6+  runs into the same trick as earlier. }
103. f6 Qg4+ 104. Kf2 Qd4+ 105. Ke2 Qe4+ 106. Kd2 Qd4+ 107. Kc1 Qf4+ 108. Kc2
Qa4+ 109. Kd3 Kg6 110. R3c4 Qd1+ 111. Kc3 Qa1+ 112. Kb4 Qb2+ 113. Ka5 Qe5+ 114.
Ka6 Qe2 115. Kb7 Kf7 116. Rb4 Qf3 117. Rb6 Qd5 118. Ka7 Qa5+ 119. Kb8 Qe5+ 120.
Rc7+ Kf8 121. f7 Qf4 122. Re6
{ It seems White is close to winning! All he has to do is play Re8+ and promote the pawn. }
122... Qb4+ 123. Rb7 Qf4+ 124. Ka8 Kg7
{ The only non-losing move!  124...Qa4+?  125.Ra7  and Black's queen is out of checks, leaving him powerless against Re8. }
125. Ree7 { Now after  125.Re8  Black has  125...Qa4+  126.Ra7  Qc6+! } 125...
Qa4+ 126. Kb8 Qf4+ 127. Rbc7 Qb4+ 128. Kc8 Qa4 129. Kb8 Qb4+ 130. Rb7 Qd6+ 131.
Rec7 Qf8+ 132. Rc8 Qd6+ 133. Ka7 Qa3+ 134. Kb6 Qb4+ 135. Kc7 Qe7+ 136. Kb8 Qd6+
137. Rcc7 Qf8+ 138. Ka7 Qa3+ 139. Kb6 Qb3+ 140. Kc6 Qe6+ 141. Kc5 Qe5+ 142. Kb6
Qd6+ 143. Rc6 Qb4+ 144. Kc7 Qe7+ 145. Kb8 Qf8+ 146. Ka7 Qa3+ 147. Ra6 Qc5+ 148.
Kb8 Qf8+ 149. Ka7 Qc5+
{ White did everything he could to win, But Black defended accurately and deserved the draw! }
