[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Alexander Morozevich vs. Viktor Laznicka"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 Qb6 8. Nd2
c5 9. c4 Qxb2 10. Rd1 Nc6
{ I think this is one of the most dangerous lines in the entire Caveman system. }
11. Ngf3 Nb4 12. Qe2 cxd4
{ In the theory section I look at  12...Nxa2  13.cxd5!  Nc3  in depth since it is quite a critical option - after all , Black is pocketing a couple of pawns plus an exchange. }
13. O-O { 13.Rb1?!  Nc2+  does not look good for White. } 13... d3
{ This pawn is quite an annoyance, but White can play around it for now. And it should be said that White's pieces have been mobilized already, while the same can't be said for Black. }
14. Qe3 Ne7 15. Rb1 Qa3 { In the theory section I look at 15... Qc3. } 16. Nd4
{ The threat of Nb5 is quite annoying. } 16... a6 17. Rb3 Qa5 18. Rfb1 Nc2
{ Perhaps  18...Ng6!  19.a3   19.cxd5  Qxd5!  20.Rxb4  Bxb4  21.Rxb4  Nxe5  looks alright for Black.  Nc2  20.Qxd3  Nxd4  21.Qxd4  Bc5  could have kept the balance. White has good compensation for the pawn. }
19. Qxd3 Nxd4 20. Qxd4
{ Compared to the variation on Black's 18th move, Black is one tempo down - which makes a world of difference. }
20... b5 { This doesn't quite seem to work. } 21. Qc5
{ I'm not sure why White rejected  21.cxb5  Nf5  22.Qb2  - he is close to winning there , having regained the sacrificed pawn while on the verge of a breakthrough on the b-file. }
21... Rc8 22. Qa7 Nc6 23. Qb7 Rc7
{ 23...Qc7!  24.Qxa6   24.Qxc7  Rxc7  25.cxb5  axb5  26.Rxb5  Kd7!  and Black has the superior endgame thanks to his better pawn structure.  bxc4  25.Rb7  Qa5  26.Re7+!  Bxe7  27.Qxc8+  Nd8  28.Bxe7  Kxe7  - White has some compensation for the pawn , but I doubt that it is enough. }
24. Qa8+ { This gains a crucial tempo. } 24... Kd7 25. cxd5 exd5 26. Rf3
{ Suddenly Black's position is falling apart. } 26... Nxe5 27. Qd8+ Kc6 28.
Qe8+ Kd6 29. Ne4+ dxe4 30. Rd1+
{ A possible finish is  30...Kc5  31.Qxe5+  Kb6  32.Be3+  Bc5  33.Rxf7!  and White has several mating threats. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ivan Saric vs. Constantin Lupulescu"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 Qb6 8. Nd2
c5 9. c4 Qxb2 10. Rb1
{ In the theory section we only look at 10. Rd1. The text is sometimes played, but I feel that the b-file should be reserved for White's queen so that in the case Black plays ...b6, White can continue to probe the light squares with Qa4+. }
10... Qxd4 11. Qa3
{ White directs the queen to the queenside anyway! More common is  11.Qe2  b6  12.Ngf3. }
11... Qxe5+ 12. Ne2 Qc7
{ For earlier mentioned reasons  12...b6!  is stronger. After  13.cxd5  Qxd5  White has sacrificed three pawns , so he will have to prove a lot! }
13. cxd5 exd5 14. Nc3 Qd7 15. O-O
{ Here too White has sacrificed three pawns, but it is easier to see that he has good compensation with all the open files and weak black pawns. }
15... Be7 16. Rfe1 Kf8 17. Re5
{ One of several promising moves  (Nf3, Nb3, Rbd1, and so on)  . } 17... Nc6
{ 17...d4  seems better. } 18. Rxd5 Qc8 19. Nde4
{ White has a clear advantage - all his pieces are active and Black has various weaknesses. White has more than enough compensation for two pawns. }
19... b6 20. Rbd1
{ With the b-file blocked it makes sense to move the b1-rook elsewhere, but e1 was perhaps a better square. }
20... Nd4
{ Now the rook is blocked on d1 as well  (unless White intends to sacrifice an exchange on d4)  . }
21. Qa4 Nf6 22. Re5 Qc7 23. Bf4
{ White's pieces are now a bit clumsily positioned, but he gets away with it. }
23... Nxe4 24. Rxe4 Qb7 25. Rde1 Ne6
{ Now that White has doubled rooks on the e-file, Black once again blocks the rooks! }
26. Nb5 { This prepares an exchange sacrifice on e6. } 26... Rd8
{ 26...Nxf4!  27.Rxf4  Kg8  and White does not have enough compensation for the two pawns. The h8-rook can be activated via h6. }
27. Rxe6 fxe6 28. Nc7 b5
{ After  28...Rh6!?  White has to be accurate:  29.Rxe6!   29.Nxe6+?  Rxe6  30.Rxe6  Rd4!  and Black wins.   29.Bxh6?  Qxc7  and Black is two pawns up.  Qc8  30.Rxh6  gxh6  31.Bxh6+  should be about equal. }
29. Qc2 Kf7
{ 29...Rc8!?  30.Nxe6+  Kg8  31.Qg6  Bf8  32.Re5  and White has some initiative for the exchange. }
30. Rxe6 Bf6 31. Qxc5
{ White is an exchange down, but his piece activity and the relative unsafe position of Black's king make up for it. }
31... Rd7 32. Rc6 Rhd8 33. Bd6 Kg8 34. g3 { 34.Ne6  was necessary. } 34... Rf7
{ 34...Rc8!  and the pin on the c-file will be decisive.  35.Qd5+  Rf7  36.Bf4  Bd8. }
35. Ne6 Re8 36. Bf4 Qd7 37. Rd6 Qc8 38. Rc6 Qd7 39. Rd6 Qc8 40. Rc6 Qd7
{ The game ended in a draw by repetition , presumably after time trouble. If Black wanted to he could have played on with  40...Qb7!?.  White has some compensation for the exchange , but Black is in no immediate trouble and in the long run he will have a passed pawn on the queenside. }
