[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Alekseev, Evgeny vs. Yevseev, Denis"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bd7
{ This is a solid move, even if it looks passive. Black intends to play ...e6 and ...c5 after which he has a French Advance type of position, in which White's pawn moves on the kingside may end up being premature. }
6. Nc3 c5 7. dxc5 e6 8. Be3 h5 9. Nb5
{ This threatens Nd6+, thus forcing Black to take the knight, but White in turn will have to make a concession on the kingside. My recommendation is to meet 8... h5 with 9. gxh5. }
9... Bxb5 10. Bxb5+ Nc6 { Now Black is threatening Qa5+ as well as hxg4. } 11.
c3 Qc7
{ 11...hxg4  12.Qxg4  Ne7  and with ...Nf5 coming Black should be alright. }
12. g5
{ The position on the kingside is now blocked, which renders White's bishop pair and space advantage as unimportant  (especially considering Black has the f5-square for his knight)  . }
12... Ne7 13. Qa4 Qxe5
{ This opens the position for White's bishops. Instead after  13...Nf5!  14.Bd4  Be7  15.O-O-O  O-O!  Black should be fine. White's extra pawn means little , and the knights are stronger than the bishops in this position. Plus it is easier for Black to start an attack on White's king than the other way around. }
14. Nf3
{ Even stronger is  14.g6!  fxg6   note that  14...Nxg6  is impossible because of  15.Bxc6+  15.Nf3  with a fantastic position for White. }
14... Qc7 15. Bf4 Qc8 16. O-O-O
{ White has obtained a close to ideal position. } 16... Ng6 17. Be3
{ Of course, White should not give up the c5-pawn easily. } 17... a6 18. Bd3
{ Now Black has to be on the lookout for the possibility of Bxg6. } 18... Qd7
19. c4
{ White starts opening the position before Black has the chance to consolidate. }
19... Nge5 { This allows White to transition to a very favorable endgame. } 20.
Nxe5
{ 20.cxd5  Nxd3+  21.Rxd3  exd5  22.Rhd1  also looks very strong , but perhaps Black can save his position with  22...Qg4! }
20... Nxe5 21. Qxd7+ Nxd7 22. b4
{ Again, White should not give up the c5-pawn lightly. } 22... dxc4 23. Bxc4
Ne5
{ Black obtains a little bit of activity with his knight, but it doesn't amount to much. }
24. Bb3 Nc6 25. Bd2
{ White defends methodically. The sharper  25.g6!?  fxg6  26.a3  was also possible. }
25... a5 26. a3 axb4 27. axb4 Nd4 28. Kb2
{ White does not hold on dogmatically to the bishop pair.  28.Bc4  b6  leads to unnecessary complications. }
28... Nxb3 29. Kxb3
{ White no longer has the bishop pair, but he kept his other advantages: his pieces are already developed and he is significantly on the way to obtaining a passed pawn on the queenside while the same can't be said for Black's majority on the kingside. }
29... Be7 30. Bc3 { An ideal position for the bishop. } 30... f6 31. Rhe1
{ Probing the newly created weakness of e6. } 31... fxg5 32. hxg5 Rd8 33. Ra1
O-O { This loses at least a pawn. } 34. Rxe6 Bxg5 35. Rg1
{ Now White has a decisive attack on the g-file. } 35... Rd5 36. Rg6
{ Presumably Black overlooked this move. } 36... Rff5 37. Rxg7+ Kf8 38. Rxb7
{ White has won two pawns and can march his c-pawn to victory. } 38... Rd3 39.
Kc4 Rdf3 40. Bg7+ Ke8 41. Re1+ Kd8 42. c6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Grandelius, Nils vs. Timman, Jan H"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bd7 6. Nc3 e6 7. Be3 Qb6 8. Nge2
{ Both sides develop in standard fashion. Note that one benefit of Black's bishop being on d7 is that ...Qxb2 most of the time does not entail a pawn sacrifice by White, as it can simply be answered with Rb1 followed by Rxb7. }
8... c5 9. Qd2
{ White should not play  dxc5  too early -  9.dxc5?!  Bxc5  10.Bxc5  Qxc5  11.Qd2  Nc6  12.f4  f6!  and White's center is being undermined. }
9... Nc6 10. O-O-O
{ This provokes Black into playing ...c4 when White's king may be subject to a pawn storm while the center is closed  (thus depriving White of adequate counterplay)  . 10. f4 is the move which I recommend in the theory section, after which White has the usual space advantage. }
10... Qa5
{ Black does not take the bait. He might have been afraid of  10...c4  11.Nf4  when White has ideas like Bxc4 dxc4 d5, or simply taking twice on d5 with his knights. }
11. dxc5
{ Here  ...c4  was a serious threat. For example:  11.f4?  c4!  12.f5  b5!  and Black's attack will arrive a lot sooner. }
11... Nxe5 12. Nd4
{ White is correctly playing for activity instead of material. } 12... Nxg4
{ Taking the other pawn with  12...Bxc5  might have been safer. } 13. Nb3 Qd8
14. Bf4 Ne7 15. Qe2
{ Here the queen interferes with the f1-bishop , which should go to  b5  or  d3.  15.Rg1  Nf6  16.Nb5  Bxb5  17.Bxb5+  Nc6  18.Qe3  seems more natural. White has full compensation for the sacrificed pawn here. }
15... Nf6 16. Nb5 Bxb5 17. Qxb5+ Qd7 18. Na5
{ White makes the best of the situation, probing the b7-pawn. We see a standard chess theme here: when two pieces are in tension  (as the two queens are here)   , it is usually better to coax your opponent into taking than performing the exchange yourself. White indeed gains nothing from  18.Qxd7+. }
18... Ng6 19. Bh2 a6 { Black in turn wants White to take on d7. } 20. Qb6
{ 20.Qxb7  Qxb7  21.Nxb7  Ne4!  is similar to the game - White regains his pawn , but passes over the initiative to Black. }
20... Qc8 21. b4 Be7 22. Qxb7
{ 22.Nxb7  is stronger. After the similar  22...Ne4  23.h5  Black cannot really commit his e7-bishop to the attack because it has to guard against the fork Nd6+. }
22... Qxb7 23. Nxb7 Ne4
{ White has regained the pawn but with this move Black takes over the initiative. }
24. h5 { 24.Bg3  Nc3!  is problematic as well. } 24... Bg5+ 25. Kb2 Nxf2 26.
Bxa6
{ White does his best to complicate the position. A lot of pieces are hanging now! }
26... Nxd1+ 27. Rxd1 Bf6+
{ Stronger is  27...Rxa6!  28.hxg6  fxg6  , but perhaps Black is scared of White's pawn mass on the queenside. }
28. Kb3 Be5 29. Nd6+ Ke7 30. hxg6 Bxh2 31. Nxf7
{ 31.Bb7!  Rab8  32.Nxf7  is similar to the text , except Black's rooks won't be positioned such that White has to give up the c5-pawn. White has good compensation for the exchange there. }
31... Rhb8 32. Be2 Ra5
{ This move makes all the difference. There is no way to protect the c5-pawn. }
33. c6 Rc5 { The c6-pawn is lost. } 34. c4 Rxc6 35. cxd5
{ It would be better for White to start pushing his a- and b-pawns. } 35...
exd5 36. Bh5 Rbc8 37. Rd3 Rc4 38. Rh3 Bf4 39. a3 d4
{ Black is clearly winning now. } 40. Ka4 Rc3 41. Rh4 { Hastening the end. }
41... Ra8+ 42. Kb5 Rb8+ 43. Ka4 Bc1 44. b5 Ra8+ { 45.Kb4  Bxa3#. } *

