[Black "Vachier Lagrave, Maxime vs. Ding, Liren"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Be4
{ Strange that a player of Ding Liren's calibre would play a variation that has such a dubious reputation. }
6. f3 Bh7 7. e6 Nf6
{ This is also possible besides 7... Qd6 and 7... fxe6, but it doesn't really solve the issue of what to do with the e6-pawn. }
8. Bf4
{ White has several good moves here. Nc3, exf7+ and Bd3 are all fine alternatives. }
8... Qb6 9. Nc3 Qxb2 { Now Nc3 and the c2-pawn are hanging as well. } 10. Kd2
{ A radical solution, but a good one. White won't have to worry about his king's safety anytime soon. }
10... Qb6
{ The queen's adventure on the kingside has cost several tempi and Black is no closer to resolving the issue of how to develop his kingside.   10...Bxc2?  11.Qxc2!  Qxa1  12.Nge2  and the queen will be trapped with Bg2 to follow. }
11. Nge2 a6
{ Perhaps  11...c5  12.Rb1  Qxe6  13.Rxb7  was a better option , but then too White retains the better chances. }
12. Rb1 Qa7 13. Na4 { Probing the newly created dark-squared weaknesses. }
13... b5 14. Nc5 Bg8 { The Caro-Kann bishop is in a sorry state. } 15. Be5 fxe6
16. Nf4 Nbd7
{ Perhaps  16...Bf7!?  was better , though it allows White to win an exchange with  17.Nfxe6  Bxe6  18.Nxe6  Kf7  19.Nc7. }
17. Nxd7 Nxd7 18. Ng6 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Rh7 20. h5
{ A funny sight. Black's bishops and the h7-rook are permanently entombed! White is of course completely winning here, though my engine doesn't understand the position and thinks Black has a slight advantage. }
20... c5 21. f4 Bf7 22. Qf3 O-O-O 23. Be2 c4 24. a4
{ It's a matter of opening up the queenside, bringing the pieces into position and mating Black's king. }
24... Kc7 25. axb5 axb5 26. Rxb5 Qd4+ 27. Ke1 Ra8 28. Rb1
{ White plays it careful.  28.Kf1  Ra1+  29.Kg2  would also have been fine. }
28... Ra2 29. c3 Qd2+ 30. Kf2 Rc2 31. Qe3
{ Though technically White is not material ahead, Black's entombed bishops and rook might as well not exist. And when you're up material, the rule is that you should exchange as many pieces as possible. Thus White forces the exchange of queens even at the cost of a pawn. }
31... Qxe3+ 32. Kxe3 Rxc3+ 33. Kd4 Rc2 34. Rhe1
{ 34.Rb5!  Rxe2  35.Rhb1  would already have led to a mating attack. } 34...
Kc6 35. Rb8
{ Notice that White doesn't even bother with Nxf8 as that would release the h7-rook from its prison. }
35... Bxg6 36. hxg6 Rh8 37. Reb1 Rd2+ 38. Ke3 Ra2 39. R8b6+
{ A possible finish is  39...Kd7  40.Kd4!  Rxe2  41.Kc5!  and Black cannot stop the threat of Rb7+ Kd8 Rb8+ Kd7 R1b7#. }
