[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Popov, Ivan vs. Arutinian, David"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Be4 6. f3 Bh7 7. e6 Qd6
{ This is more standard than the ...Nf6 of the previous game. } 8. exf7+ Kxf7
9. f4
{ This not only stops ...Qg3+, but also the freeing advance ...e5  (which is the main idea behind Black's ...Qd6 move)  . }
9... Nf6 10. Nf3
{ White's pawn moves have achieved a lot, but also come at a cost. He is behind in development and has some weaknesses in his position to deal with. The text sacrifices the g4-pawn while preventing Black from achieving anything with ...Qe6+. }
10... Nxg4 11. h5
{ This clamps down on the g6-square and also prevents Black from cementing his g4-knight with ...h5. }
11... Bf5
{ I am not a fan of this move. White will soon play Bd3 when the light-squared bishops will probably be exchanged anyway, and in that case this move will amount to a loss of tempo. }
12. Nc3 Qe6+ 13. Ne5+ Nxe5 14. fxe5
{ It is time to take stock. White has sacrificed a pawn. In return he has displaced Black's king and obtained a significant space advantage on the kingside. Moreover, Black's queen is positioned kind of clumsily - preventing Black from developing his kingside with ...e6 and ...Bb4. All in all, if White simply develops he will very easily develop a promising attack on the kingside. }
14... g5 15. hxg6+
{ Of course White does not allow Black to turn his g7-weakness into a strength on g5. }
15... Qxg6 16. Be3 Ke8
{ 16...Bxc2  is too risky:  17.Qe2!  Na6  18.Rg1  Qf5  (the only move, protecting the bishop as well as guarding against Qh5+)  19.Rg3  Ke8  20.Bh3  Qh7  21.Nxd5!  with a winning attack. }
17. Rg1 Qf7 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 { White is already close to winning. } 19...
Rg8
{ Exchanging this rook does not help Black much - it exchanges an attacker, but also a defender. }
20. O-O-O Rxg1 21. Rxg1 Na6 22. Rf1 Nb4 23. Qd1 Qg6 24. a3 Na6 25. Qf3 Kd7
{ This loses directly. After  25...Qg8  26.Ne2  Nc7  27.Nf4  Rd8  Black's position is very unpleasant but not yet lost. }
26. Nxd5 Nc7
{ 26...cxd5  27.Qxd5+  Kc7  28.e6!  gives White a winning attack due to the double threat Qd7+ and Bf4+. }
27. Nf4 Qf5 28. Qg2
{ Threatening  Ng6.  After  28...Qh7  29.e6+!  Ke8   29...Nxe6  30.Nxe6  Kxe6  31.Qg4+  does not end well  30.Ng6  Bg7  31.Rf7  is decisive. }
