[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Yudasin, Leonid vs. Sapis, Witalis"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 c5
{ Playing ...c5 in combination with ...Bf5 this early is too ambitious. } 5.
dxc5 Nc6
{ The main issue is that Black cannot play  5...e6?  yet because the usual trap  6.g4  Bg6  7.h5  still works. Black should first provide a safe square for this bishop and only then worry about playing ...c5! }
6. Bb5 { 6.Nf3  Bg4  would make Black's life considerably easier. } 6... Qa5+
7. Nc3 O-O-O
{ The fact that Black cannot play ...e6 limits him in the way he can develop. }
8. Bxc6 { This is necessary as Black was threatening ...d4. } 8... bxc6 9. Qd4
{ Setting up a blockade on the dark squares. } 9... h5
{ 9...Bxc2  was possible , but would have been met by  10.e6!  fxe6  11.Nf3  and White has a fantastic position. After the text Black is finally ready to play ..e6, but he is a bit late! }
10. b4 Qa6 11. a4
{ Threatening to launch a deadly attack on Black's king with b5. } 11... Qc4
{ Black flees into an endgame a pawn down. } 12. Qxc4 dxc4 13. Ra2
{ This looks like an ugly way to defend the c2-pawn, but eventually White will reroute the c3-knight and play the pawn to c3 when the rook can join play again. }
13... e6 14. a5
{ This looks ugly too, but Black was threatening to break up White's queenside pawn formation with ...a5. }
14... Ne7 15. Nf3 Nd5 16. Nxd5 Rxd5 17. O-O Be7 18. Be3 Rhd8 19. c3
{ White has consolidated his position and is simply a pawn up. } 19... Bd3 20.
Re1 a6 21. Bg5
{ White would like to exchange the dark-squared bishops, when his knight would have uncontested squares like d4 and d6. }
21... f6 22. Bf4
{ Also promising is the exchange sacrifice  22.exf6  gxf6  23.Rxe6!  Kd7  24.Rxf6  Bxf6  25.Bxf6  - White has three pawns and control over the dark squares for the exchange. }
22... Bf5 23. Rae2 Rd3 24. Re3 Bg4 25. Nd4 fxe5 26. Bxe5 Bxh4 27. g3
{ This leads to some complications, but Yudasin seems to have calculately them accurately  (or did he? see the note to Black's 32th move)   . The calmer option was  27.Bxg7  Rg8  28.Be5  when White keeps a clear advantage. }
27... Bg5 28. f4 Bf6 29. Nxc6
{ This is what White wanted to play, but he first had to make some space for his king  (with g3 and f4)  . }
29... Rxe3 30. Rxe3 Rd1+ 31. Kf2 Rd2+ 32. Kf1 Rd1+
{ 32...h4!  seems to lead to a draw.  33.gxh4  (White really cannot allow this pawn to get to h3)  Rd1+  34.Re1   34.Kg2  Rd2+  35.Kg3  Rd3  36.Kxg4!?  Rxe3  37.Bxf6  gxf6  is an interesting try if White wants to play on , but the evaluation of this position is highly unclear.  Bh3+  35.Ke2  Bg4+  36.Kf1  Bh3+  is a repetition of moves. }
33. Re1 Rd3 34. b5 { Breaking through. } 34... axb5 35. a6 Bf3
{ Playing for passive defense is rarely a good idea in endgames , but here the more active option would have lost too:  35...h4!?  36.Na7+  Kd7  37.c6+  Ke8  (any other square for the king and White can exchange on f6 and take the h4-pawn)  38.Rb1!  making space for his king; Black was threatening a repetition a moves starting with Rf3+. White will play c7-c8 next. }
36. Nd4 Rxc3 37. Nxb5 { 37.c6! } 37... Rb3 38. Nd4 Ra3
{ Black misses his final chance:  38...Rd3!  39.Nxe6  c3  with some counterplay. }
39. Bxf6 gxf6 40. Rxe6 Bd5 41. Rxf6
{ The position has cleared up. White is two pawns up and Black's c-pawn is not lethal. }
41... c3 42. Ke2 Bc4+ 43. Ke3 Bxa6 44. Nc2 Ra4 45. Rh6 Ra2 46. Nb4 Re2+ 47. Kd4
Bb5 { 47...c2  48.Nxc2  Rxc2  49.Rxa6. } 48. Kxc3 Re3+ 49. Kd4 Rxg3 50. c6 Rg8
51. Kc5
{ Technically  White is only a pawn up, but the difference in king activity makes all the difference. Black will soon face mate threats. }
51... Be2 52. Nd5 Rf8 53. Rh7 Kb8 54. Kb6
{ White intends to play Ra7, Nc7 and Ra8# and it is not clear what Black can do about it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sutovsky, Emil vs. Egeli, Per Ove"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nc3 Qb6 5. h4
{ Via an alternate move order we reach a type of Caveman position in which Black has played an early ...Qb6. }
5... h5 6. Nge2 e6 7. Ng3 Bg6 8. Be2
{ An alternative is  8.Na4!?  Qa5+  9.c3  when White intends to follow up with b4 to establish control over the c5-square. }
8... c5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. O-O
{ White's threat to take on h5 is not that much of a threat, because after taking Black can play ...Bxh5, ...g6 and ...Rxh4 winning back his pawn. }
10... Nc6 11. Bxh5 { 11.Na4!?  is again an alternative. } 11... Bxh5 12. Nxh5
g6 13. Nf4 Rxh4 14. g3 Rh7 15. Na4 Qb5 16. Nxc5 Qxc5 17. Nd3 Qc4
{ Objectively White has not achieved that much from the opening. Black doesn't have that many weaknesses and can easily finish his development by playing Ne7-f5 and O-O-O. }
18. Re1 Nge7 19. b3 Qa6
{ The queen will be out of play here. Better is  19...Qb5  when Black can answer  20.Bg5  with  20...d4  21.Qf3  Qd5  , when the position is about equal. }
20. Bg5 O-O-O 21. Bf6
{ The bishop has a dominant position. Its control over h8 allows White to take control over the h-file next. }
21... Qb6 22. Kg2 Rd7 23. Qd2 d4 24. Rh1 Rxh1 25. Rxh1 Nd5
{ Black is slightly too late with this maneuver! } 26. Rh8+ Kc7 27. Qh6 Nxf6
28. exf6 Qb5 29. Qf8
{ White has taken full control over the 8th rank. While the computer may say the position is about equal, in practice it is extremely difficult for Black to defend this position. }
29... Qd5+ 30. Kg1 e5
{ Black makes good use of his main trump - his strong pawn center. } 31. Qc8+
Kb6 32. Nb2 e4
{ Black should probably have pre-emptively played  32...Ka6  33.Na4  Rd6!  though White can continue to probe with a3, b4 and Nc5. }
33. Na4+ Ka5
{ Presumably Black missed that   33...Ka6 ?  isn't possible now because of  34.Qxd7!  Qxd7  35.Nc5+. }
34. Nc5 { Now Black's position seems to be falling apart. } 34... d3 35. c4 Qd4
{ Here the computer comes up with the exchange sacrifice  35...Qxc5!  36.Qxd7  Kb4!!  when White has to be careful to hold the balance. Black's king will be safe behind White's queenside pawns while the d3-pawn is very close to being promoted. }
36. b4+ { A strong in-between move which opens up the b-file. } 36... Kxb4
{ 36...Nxb4?  37.Nb3+. } 37. Nxd7 d2 { 37...e3!  was the final chance. } 38.
Qxb7+
{ Now  38...Kc3  is impossible because the d2-pawn blocks the escape of Black's king:  39.Qb3#. }
38... Qb6 39. Nxb6 d1=Q+ 40. Kh2 Nd4 41. Nd5+
{ 41...Kxc4  42.Rc8+  Kd3  43.Nf4+  Kd2  44.Qb4#  is the end. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Short, Nigel D vs. Speelman, Jonathan S"]
[Result "*"]

{ At the time of this game, Nigel Short was a 14-year old with a rating of 2260, and Jonathan Speelman was a 22-year old IM. Of course, later on Short would become a world championship contender, and Speelman would become a strong grandmaster. }
1. e4 c6 2. Ne2
{ This is a more usual move order by which my recommendation against 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 comes on the board. }
2... d5 3. e5 c5 4. d4
{ Thus we get a Botvinnik-Carls Caro-Kann on the board. } 4... Nc6 5. c3 Bf5 6.
dxc5 Nxe5 7. Nd4 Bd7 8. Be2 e6 9. b4
{ An interesting position. Black has two center pawns to none, but White has a large pawn mass on the queenside and free development for his pieces where Black is a bit cramped. There are chances for both sides in such a position. }
9... Nf6 10. O-O Be7 11. Be3 O-O 12. Nd2 Qc7 13. f4
{ Both sides have developed calmly, and White decides the time is right for an advance on the kingside. }
13... Ng6 14. Qe1 b6 15. N4b3 Ba4 16. Rc1 Rfe8
{ Black has a promising exchange sacrifice here in  16...bxc5  17.Nxc5  Bxc5  18.Bxc5   18.bxc5!?  Nxf4!  19.Bxf8  Rxf8.  Black has good play on the dark squares. }
17. Qf2 { Now White has both c5 and f4 well protected. } 17... Bxb3
{ This exchange is a bit premature - perhaps  17...Rab8  first is better. } 18.
axb3 Rab8 19. cxb6 axb6 20. Bd4 Nd7 21. Bb5
{ White has a small advantage - a bit more space and better placed pieces. }
21... Bd6 22. g3 Re7 23. Nf3 { 23.c4!?  was a more active option here. } 23...
Nc5 24. Qc2 Ne4 25. Qd3 e5
{ This pawn break activates Black's pieces. The position is equal now. } 26.
fxe5 Nxe5 27. Nxe5 Bxe5 28. c4 Bxd4+
{ 28...Qd6!  29.cxd5  Qxd5  and it is likely that soon a drawn endgame will arise. }
29. Qxd4 { Now the tension c4-d5 is in White's favor. } 29... Rc8 30. Kg2 h5
{ The decisive mistake. } 31. cxd5 Qxc1 32. Rxc1 Rxc1 33. Bd3
{ The issue is that the e4-knight now has no good squares.  33...Nd6  34.Qf4!  forks c1-rook and d6-knight, while almost any other move allows White to play d6. }
33... Re1 34. d6
{ Black loses material because he cannot defend both the e4-knight and the d6-d7-d8 advance. }
34... Nxd6 35. Qxd6 R1e6 36. Qd5 g6 37. b5 Ra7 38. b4 Kg7 39. Bc4 Rf6 40. Qe5
{ A possible finish is  40...Ra3  41.h3  Raf3  42.g4  hxg4  43.hxg4  Kg8  44.Be2!  Rf2+  45.Kg3  Kh7  46.Qd4  and Black cannot escape the exchange of queen for two rooks. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Baklan, Vladimir vs. Fier, Alexandr"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Ne2 Nc6 5. c3 Bg4
{ This is quite an annoying move.  6.f3  is possible , but after  6...Bf5  we have an inferior version of the 5... Bf5 variation - the pawn on f3 allows tactics based on Qh4+. }
6. h3 Bxe2
{ Now the position becomes static - White has the bishop pair and a space advantage, but Black has no weaknesses and the bishop pair doesn't mean much with the center closed. }
7. Bxe2 e6 8. O-O Nge7 9. Na3
{ In the French defense  (with the same pawn structure)  this development of the knight is a common answer to Black playing Nge7-f5. }
9... Nf5 10. Nc2 Be7 11. Bd3 { White's plan is a bit crude but effective. }
11... g6 12. Bxf5 gxf5 { 12...exf5  would leave the d5-pawn chronically weak. }
13. Qh5
{ Now the h7-pawn will always be a liability, and it is not obvious yet how Black is going to solve the problem of his king's safety. }
13... cxd4
{ 13...Qb6  would allow  14.dxc5  Bxc5  15.b4  Be7  16.Be3  and it looks scary for Black to try to castle queenside. }
14. Nxd4 { Threatening Nxe6. } 14... Qd7
{ 14...Nxd4  15.cxd4  would be clearly better to White. } 15. Bh6 Rg8 16. Bf4
Rg7 17. Rfd1 O-O-O 18. c4 Rdg8
{ Black has some pressure. The problem is that with the compromised pawn-structure he doesn't have too many ways to attack, and once his attack runs out, it is only White who has opportunities to attack the enemy king. }
19. g3 Bg5 20. Qf3 Bxf4 21. Qxf4 Ne7 22. Nb5 Kb8 23. Qe3 b6 24. a4
{ White has a strong attack. } 24... Qc6
{ 24...h5!?  25.a5  h4  26.axb6  Rxg3+!  27.fxg3  Rxg3+  sees Black obtain good counterchances. However, White can play more patiently with moves like 25. Qf4 or 25. Qd4 when it is not obvious how Black can make progress on the kingside. }
25. Nd4 Qb7 26. a5 dxc4 27. axb6 Qxb6 28. Qa3
{ 28.Ra4!  Nd5  29.Qa3  and White has a winning attack according to the computer. He is threatening Ra5-b5 among other moves. }
28... Nd5
{ Now however White's pieces - especially his rooks - are poorly positioned for an attack on Black's king, while Black in turn is threatening ...f4. Therefore White decides to flee into an endgame. }
29. Qd6+ Qxd6 30. exd6 f4 31. d7 Kb7 32. Nf5 exf5
{ The only move , as after  32...Rg6?  33.Nd6+  Kc7  34.Nxf7  (threatening to promote)  Kxd7  35.Ne5+  White wins the exchange. }
33. Rxd5 Rd8 34. Rb5+ Kc6 35. Rxf5 fxg3 36. Rxa7 Kb6
{ Black wins the d7-pawn and the position that remains is a dead draw. } 37.
Ra4 Rxd7 38. Rb4+ Kc7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Mamedov, Rauf vs. Prohaszka, Peter"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Ne2 d5 3. e5 c5 4. d4 Nc6 5. c3 cxd4 6. cxd4 Bf5 7. Nbc3 e6 8. Ng3
{ Playing Nge2 over Nf3 in the Caro-Kann Advance has the advantage that Black has more difficulties with his light-squared bishop. With the knight on f3, he can  (and often does)  play the bishop to g4 and just exchange it for the knight. But the knight on g3 harasses the bishop and supports the pawn advances f4-f5 and h4-h5. }
8... Bg6 9. h4 h5 10. Be3
{ Of course, having the knight on g3 has some disadvantages as well. One is that the d4-pawn is less well protected, which makes Be3 a necessity. }
10... Qb6 11. Qd2 Nh6 12. Be2 Nf5
{ Perhaps  12...Be7  is better. Black does not have to be scared of  13.Bxh5  Bxh5  14.Nxh5  Nf5  , as he will win back the h-pawn next move. }
13. Nxf5 Bxf5 14. Rc1 Be7
{ 14...Bb4  15.a3  Be7  leads to similar play as in the game. } 15. Na4
{ This seems like the only way to make some progress in the position. } 15...
Qb4
{ 15...Qa5!?  16.Qxa5  Nxa5  17.b3  seems stronger , though White is still a little bit better. }
16. Nc5 Bxc5 { This surrenders control over the dark squares to White. } 17.
Rxc5 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2
{ An endgame has arisen in which White is clearly better. He is better developed and has an unopposed dark-squared bishop. }
18... Kd7 19. b4 Bg6
{ 19...Nxb4?  20.Rb5  would see White's rook enter the 7th rank decisively. }
20. Rhc1 Rhc8 21. a3
{ White does need to be careful:  21.a4?!  Nxb4  22.Rb5  Rxc1  23.Kxc1  Rc8+  24.Kd1  Nc2!  25.Rxb7+  Rc7  and his advantage is gone. }
21... a6 22. g4
{ White cannot make further progress on the queenside, so he turns his attention to the kingside. }
22... hxg4 23. Bxg4 Ne7 { Necessary because White was threatening Rxd5+! } 24.
h5 Be4 25. Bg5 b6
{ Now exchanging all the rooks on c8 would lead to a probably drawn position. }
26. Bxe7 { A courageous decision. White sacrifices the exchange for a pawn. }
26... bxc5 27. Bxc5 g6
{ Black wisely offers his g-pawn for exchange. In the long run it could have become a weakness on g7. }
28. hxg6 Bxg6 29. Be2 Rh8 30. a4 Rh2 31. Ke3 Rh3+ 32. f3 Rh2 33. Bd6 Rc8 34.
Bc5 Ra8 35. b5 Rxe2+
{ Black returns the exchange. No doubt he was afraid that the bishop pair would steamroll the a-pawn to victory after  35...axb5  36.Bxb5+  Kd8  37.Bb6+  Ke7  38.a5.  But I don't see how White can make progress after  38...Rb2  39.Rc5  Rb8! }
36. Kxe2 axb5 37. axb5
{ Now White has an extra pawn, but he has to watch out for cases in which the factor of the opposite-colored bishops makes for a draw. }
37... Ra2+ 38. Ke3 Rb2
{ Black should not give up control over the a-file. After   38...Kc7  39.b6+  Kb7  40.Rh1  Ra8  41.Kf4  Ra4  42.Kg5  Ra2  43.Kf6  Ra8  44.Rg1  Rg8!  (Not allowing White to sacrifice the exchange again)  45.Ra1   Perhaps  45.f4  will win.  (Ra8! and White is not making progress.) }
39. b6 Rb3+ 40. Kf4 Kc6 41. Ra1 { Now Black is lost. } 41... Bh5 42. Ra7 Kb5
43. Kg5 Bg6 44. f4 Rb1 45. Kf6 Kc6 46. Ke7
{ 46.Rc7+  Kb5  47.Rxf7!  also wins directly. } 46... Rxb6
{ Another exchange sac, but this will not save Black. } 47. Bxb6 Kxb6 48. Ra3
Kb5 49. Rc3 { Blocking Black's king on the c-file. } 49... Kb4 50. Rc5 Kb3 51.
Kf6 Kb4 52. Rc6 Kb5 53. Rxe6 Kc4
{ 53...fxe6  54.Kxg6  Kc4  55.f5  and White wins. } 54. Rc6+ Kxd4 55. f5 Bh5
56. e6 fxe6 57. fxe6 Ke3 58. e7 d4 59. Rc8 d3 60. Rh8
{ The only winning move here. The bishop is forced away from the e8-square, after which White promotes with check. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kasparov, Garry vs. Kaiumov, Dmitry D"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Ne2 d5 3. e5 c5 4. d4 Nc6 5. c3 e6
{ This move makes the game transpose to a type of French Advance in which White has an extra move  (because Black played ...c5 in two moves)  but also is stuck with an early Ne2  (not necessarily good for him)  . }
6. Nd2
{ Kasparov decides to bring the b1-knight over to f3 so the d4-pawn is adequately protected. }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Nh6 8. Nf3 Nf5 9. a3
{ This move is usually a necessity to start operations on the queenside in the French Advance. The c6-knight and f8-bishop would both like access to the b4-square. }
9... Qb6
{ Perhaps  9...Bd7  is more accurate , so that  10.g4  can be answered with  10...Nh4. }
10. g4 { Now the knight is kicked backwards. } 10... Nfe7
{ This knight will lead a sorry life this game. } 11. Nf4
{ A flexible square for the knight - it could go to either kingside or queenside. }
11... Na5 12. Rb1 Nb3 13. Be3 Bd7 14. Bd3 Rc8 15. Bc2 Na5 16. Kf1 Nc4 17. Bc1
{ Several moves of slow maneuvering have gone by. If Black now plays  17...Nc6!  , pressurizing the d4-pawn , his position seems fine. }
17... Bb5 { Black threatens a discovered check, but this move lacks purpose. }
18. Kg2
{ White's king steps out of the way and the bishop on b5 just looks silly now. }
18... Qc7 19. Bd3 Bd7 20. b3
{ Now White is driving back Black's pieces and making real progress. } 20...
Na5 21. Bd2 Qb6 22. Nh5
{ The knight is a real nuisance here - it attacks the g7-pawn and, should Black play ...g6, the knight can move to f6. }
22... Bb5 23. Bb4 Bxd3
{ Black exchanges his bad bishop, but his position is still much worse. } 24.
Qxd3 Nac6 25. Bc5 Qa6 26. Qe3
{ Of course, Kasparov does not agree to exchange queens. } 26... b6 27. Bd6 Ng6
28. Bxf8 Kxf8 29. Rhc1
{ Though it wasn't necessary in this position, Kasparov never shirks away from sacrificing a pawn. }
29... Qxa3 30. Rc3 Qe7 31. Rbc1 Qd7 32. b4 Nge7
{ Black cracks under the pressure. After  32...a5!  33.bxa5  bxa5  White is clearly better , but he has yet to find a way to break through Black's defenses. }
33. Nf6 Qd8
{ This loses , but taking on  f6  wasn't any better:  33...gxf6  34.exf6  Ng6   34...Ng8  35.Ne5!  is another point of the piece sac - the e5-square is cleared for White's remaining knight.  35.b5!  regains the piece with a decisive advantage. }
34. b5 Na5 { This leads to a quick end. } 35. Rxc8 Nxc8 36. Rxc8
{ 36...Qxc8  37.Qa3+  and Black has to give up his queen to prevent mate. } *

